Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.988 --> 00:00:02.964
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:04.940 --> 00:00:05.930
Stanford University.

00:00:12.030 --> 00:00:14.423
OK, let's get started.

00:00:18.590 --> 00:00:22.790
We pick up with aggression,
competition, et cetera.

00:00:22.790 --> 00:00:25.390
And where have we gotten to?

00:00:25.390 --> 00:00:28.130
We are now just about
to leap to, instead

00:00:28.130 --> 00:00:32.100
of early environment,
early hormonal exposure,

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:37.240
parenatal-- hormones both
pre, before and after birth.

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:39.300
Around that time,
what do they have

00:00:39.300 --> 00:00:42.120
to do with adult
behavior in these realms?

00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:45.170
So, again, this is tapping into
that same concept from the sex

00:00:45.170 --> 00:00:48.840
lectures-- organizational
hormonal effects,

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:51.100
versus activational.

00:00:51.100 --> 00:00:55.250
Organizational early in life,
setting up the nervous system

00:00:55.250 --> 00:01:00.330
to respond later on to some
sort of activational hormonal

00:01:00.330 --> 00:01:01.890
effect.

00:01:01.890 --> 00:01:04.744
So the basic theme that's come
through with animal studies

00:01:04.744 --> 00:01:07.100
here has been built
around, what if you

00:01:07.100 --> 00:01:12.600
have females who are prenatally,
or perinatally, androgenized,

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:15.270
exposed to high
testosterone levels?

00:01:15.270 --> 00:01:18.130
And what you see is,
basically, the exact same thing

00:01:18.130 --> 00:01:20.210
as from the sex
lectures, which is

00:01:20.210 --> 00:01:22.190
you get a powerful
masculinization--

00:01:22.190 --> 00:01:28.870
organizational masculinization
effect so that later on these

00:01:28.870 --> 00:01:32.340
are females who respond
to even their low levels

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:34.090
of testosterone
in the bloodstream

00:01:34.090 --> 00:01:36.360
with increased
levels of aggression,

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:40.270
more aggressive play, bunch
of measures like that,

00:01:40.270 --> 00:01:43.820
less maternal behavior when
having offspring-- a pretty

00:01:43.820 --> 00:01:47.370
clear literature in terms
of prenatal masculinization

00:01:47.370 --> 00:01:52.110
of aggressive behavior, as
well as sexual behavior.

00:01:52.110 --> 00:01:55.390
So, as usual, what about humans?

00:01:55.390 --> 00:01:57.690
And we go back to
our two diseases

00:01:57.690 --> 00:02:01.550
from the other week one was that
congenital adrenal hyperplasia

00:02:01.550 --> 00:02:04.580
business, that tumor in
the mother that produces

00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:07.140
vast amounts of,
among other things,

00:02:07.140 --> 00:02:10.310
an androgen, a
testosterone derivative,

00:02:10.310 --> 00:02:13.730
which androgenizes the fetus.

00:02:13.730 --> 00:02:17.070
Or the case with that drug
DES, diethylstilbestrol,

00:02:17.070 --> 00:02:18.790
where some women in
the '50s took them

00:02:18.790 --> 00:02:21.470
for preventing
miscarriage, in some cases

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:22.920
had androgenic effect.

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:25.260
Back to the same
issue as with the sex

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:29.510
lectures, so what's the behavior
of these individuals like?

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:32.480
And, again, people
were over that one.

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:35.200
People were really
interested in this.

00:02:35.200 --> 00:02:37.030
Both of them kind of
burst on the scene,

00:02:37.030 --> 00:02:40.840
congenital adrenal hyperplasia,
and the DES babies,

00:02:40.840 --> 00:02:43.620
around the same time
lots of people started

00:02:43.620 --> 00:02:47.230
studying these kids as they
started growing up with a very

00:02:47.230 --> 00:02:49.840
simple question
here of, are they

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:53.770
going to be more aggressive
than typical girls?

00:02:53.770 --> 00:02:56.214
And, ultimately, will they
be more aggressive women?

00:02:56.214 --> 00:02:57.880
And somewhere between
the lines, they're

00:02:57.880 --> 00:02:59.770
also asking the
question, are they

00:02:59.770 --> 00:03:03.950
going to be more aggressive than
is normal for a typical girl?

00:03:03.950 --> 00:03:06.500
So what began to come
out of these studies?

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:10.420
First off, some interesting,
odd, quirky things-- one

00:03:10.420 --> 00:03:15.430
is when you androgenize
a female fetus

00:03:15.430 --> 00:03:18.790
human, later on as
a child she will

00:03:18.790 --> 00:03:22.754
have a higher than average IQ.

00:03:22.754 --> 00:03:25.770
Whoa, that's kind
of interesting.

00:03:25.770 --> 00:03:29.080
Stay tuned, it turns out
that's not at all interesting.

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:31.150
OK, so that was observed.

00:03:31.150 --> 00:03:33.150
Another thing,
more of a tendency

00:03:33.150 --> 00:03:37.190
towards being left-handed,
better spatial skills.

00:03:37.190 --> 00:03:39.370
And both of those
are attributes that

00:03:39.370 --> 00:03:42.150
are more common among
males than females.

00:03:42.150 --> 00:03:43.870
What else?

00:03:43.870 --> 00:03:45.910
That's all that
sort of stuff having

00:03:45.910 --> 00:03:48.330
to do with ancillary issues.

00:03:48.330 --> 00:03:51.970
But now, finally, people
were then really focusing

00:03:51.970 --> 00:03:53.910
in on the issues of aggression.

00:03:53.910 --> 00:03:56.170
And by the time these
girls were, I don't know,

00:03:56.170 --> 00:04:01.280
10, 12 years old or so, the
findings were absolutely clear.

00:04:01.280 --> 00:04:07.090
These kids were way, way
more aggressive than normal.

00:04:07.090 --> 00:04:08.800
How do you know?

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:12.280
Because they were less
interested in playing

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:15.820
with dolls than normal
girls, because they expressed

00:04:15.820 --> 00:04:18.510
less interest in
marriage, because they

00:04:18.510 --> 00:04:21.910
expressed more interest in
having a career some day.

00:04:21.910 --> 00:04:26.250
So these were, obviously, over
the top, rabid, psychopathic,

00:04:26.250 --> 00:04:30.050
androgenized, females
because they weren't normal.

00:04:30.050 --> 00:04:32.120
They weren't interested
in dolls, or marriage,

00:04:32.120 --> 00:04:33.530
and were interested in a career.

00:04:33.530 --> 00:04:37.250
This was in every textbook
starting in the late '60s,

00:04:37.250 --> 00:04:40.400
and was still there in
textbooks by the mid '80s or so,

00:04:40.400 --> 00:04:42.000
endocrinology textbooks.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.280
And somewhere in the
early '70s or so,

00:04:45.280 --> 00:04:48.000
probably some male
endocrinologists kind of

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.730
discovered that,
you know, wanting

00:04:50.730 --> 00:04:54.930
a career if you're female
does not count as aggression.

00:04:54.930 --> 00:04:57.810
Actually, they came up with an
even better term-- assertive

00:04:57.810 --> 00:04:59.050
dominance.

00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:02.480
How's that for a term that just
summarizes an entire worldview

00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:04.240
of gender differences?

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:07.730
OK, so some male endocrinologist
finally figured that out.

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:09.290
Or maybe actually
they're finally

00:05:09.290 --> 00:05:11.680
started being some female
endocrinologists who

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:13.250
pointed out this was gibberish.

00:05:13.250 --> 00:05:16.060
The entire literature
went down the tubes,

00:05:16.060 --> 00:05:18.240
had to be started all over.

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:21.870
Oh, wanting a career is not
being assertively, dominantly

00:05:21.870 --> 00:05:24.290
aggressive if you're female.

00:05:24.290 --> 00:05:27.730
So back to stage one on that
whole literature, lots of work

00:05:27.730 --> 00:05:28.560
since then.

00:05:28.560 --> 00:05:31.130
What the literature
has generally shown

00:05:31.130 --> 00:05:34.910
is the left-handedness is there.

00:05:34.910 --> 00:05:36.650
The spatial issue
seem to remain.

00:05:39.250 --> 00:05:41.420
The higher IQ is there.

00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:43.290
What's up with that?

00:05:43.290 --> 00:05:45.790
All that's known is
as an explanation,

00:05:45.790 --> 00:05:49.890
you find an equivalently
higher IQ in the parents.

00:05:49.890 --> 00:05:52.460
So it's got nothing to do
with the androgenization.

00:05:52.460 --> 00:05:56.550
There's some sort of
selection going on, perhaps

00:05:56.550 --> 00:06:00.370
who winds up being in a study
like this-- sort of more

00:06:00.370 --> 00:06:01.460
educated families.

00:06:01.460 --> 00:06:02.440
Who knows what.

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:05.190
But that one turned out
to be a red herring.

00:06:05.190 --> 00:06:06.570
What about aggression?

00:06:06.570 --> 00:06:08.750
Because now there's
been populations

00:06:08.750 --> 00:06:12.430
of androgenized girls who
are now well into adulthood.

00:06:12.430 --> 00:06:14.160
What about antisocial behavior?

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:16.080
What about all those
sorts of things?

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:20.280
And, in general, what is shown
is there's not much going on.

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:23.480
The literature has
been pretty ambiguous

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:27.490
in terms of any sort of trends
there of different behaviors,

00:06:27.490 --> 00:06:31.230
different attitudes, different
motivations, et cetera,

00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:34.490
in these folks as they grow up.

00:06:34.490 --> 00:06:39.310
But suppose what you
found was, as adults,

00:06:39.310 --> 00:06:42.640
women who had been androgenized
as fetuses were now

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:47.260
17 times more likely to
start brawls in bar rooms,

00:06:47.260 --> 00:06:50.760
to snipe at people
from the tops of water

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:52.310
towers, things of that sort.

00:06:52.310 --> 00:06:53.652
What would you conclude?

00:06:53.652 --> 00:06:56.700
Oh, prenatal testosterone
makes you more

00:06:56.700 --> 00:06:59.900
aggressive as an adult-- no.

00:06:59.900 --> 00:07:02.820
Same confound with these
folks as from the sex

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:07.020
lectures the other week, which
is these girls were not just

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:10.570
born having been exposed to
lots of testosterone in utero,

00:07:10.570 --> 00:07:13.020
and doing something or
other to their brain.

00:07:13.020 --> 00:07:17.520
They were born with, basically,
a hermaphroditic profile

00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:21.390
of genitals that looked
like males, or intersects,

00:07:21.390 --> 00:07:23.700
sexually ambiguous genitals.

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:26.320
These were the kids who
went through a dozen rounds

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:30.070
of reconstructive surgery in
their first half dozen years

00:07:30.070 --> 00:07:33.810
of life, their first 10 years of
life, in this part of the body

00:07:33.810 --> 00:07:36.890
that everyone is interested in,
but doesn't quite talk about.

00:07:36.890 --> 00:07:38.070
And what's up with that?

00:07:38.070 --> 00:07:39.460
Why aren't I normal?

00:07:39.460 --> 00:07:42.580
And these, once
again, were not girls

00:07:42.580 --> 00:07:44.960
who grew up with the only
thing being different

00:07:44.960 --> 00:07:48.050
about them their prenatal
hormone exposure.

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:52.070
Basically makes the whole
literature uninterpretable.

00:07:52.070 --> 00:07:54.850
So what else in terms of
prenatal hormone effects?

00:07:54.850 --> 00:07:56.580
Another literature
that people have

00:07:56.580 --> 00:07:59.420
looked at, which in
principle could be extremely

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:03.460
informative, looking
at dizygotic twins,

00:08:03.460 --> 00:08:05.190
non-identical twins.

00:08:05.190 --> 00:08:06.580
So you were a girl.

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:08.550
You're a dizygotic twin.

00:08:08.550 --> 00:08:11.080
And you could have a
sibling who is either

00:08:11.080 --> 00:08:14.000
a sister or a brother.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:17.270
In other words, you may have
spent your time in utero

00:08:17.270 --> 00:08:20.800
with your sibling who
either did or did not

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:24.070
secrete a certain amount of
testosterone during that time.

00:08:24.070 --> 00:08:26.600
Do you see any sort
of masculinization

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:30.100
of aspects of
aggressive behavior

00:08:30.100 --> 00:08:34.710
in girls who are dizygotic
twins with a male sibling

00:08:34.710 --> 00:08:36.929
rather than a female one?

00:08:36.929 --> 00:08:40.929
And what you wind up
seeing is these kids show,

00:08:40.929 --> 00:08:44.370
on the average, more
aggressive play in childhood,

00:08:44.370 --> 00:08:46.850
more-- here's the
jargony term-- more rough

00:08:46.850 --> 00:08:51.420
and tumble play, more interest
in cars, mechanical things

00:08:51.420 --> 00:08:55.420
like that, less interest in
stuffed animals, in dolls--

00:08:55.420 --> 00:08:57.410
small effect, very small effect.

00:08:57.410 --> 00:09:01.030
Nonetheless, it suggests that
this is another realm where

00:09:01.030 --> 00:09:04.120
a little bit of prenatal
exposure to testosterone

00:09:04.120 --> 00:09:07.590
will change the
behavioral profile.

00:09:07.590 --> 00:09:10.980
Except there's a confound
in these studies, which

00:09:10.980 --> 00:09:15.100
is if you were a girl and you
have an identical twin who

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:19.890
is a boy, you are in the
Guinness Book of Records.

00:09:19.890 --> 00:09:21.470
OK, let's start that one.

00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:25.160
If you are a girl and you
have a non-identical twin--

00:09:25.160 --> 00:09:26.302
that's how it works, OK.

00:09:26.302 --> 00:09:28.510
I knew I should have checked
the notes before coming.

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:31.880
So you've got a non-identical
twin who is a boy.

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:35.390
Not only do you spend
your prenatal environment

00:09:35.390 --> 00:09:37.870
being awash in some of
his dribbling hormones,

00:09:37.870 --> 00:09:39.940
but you grow up with him.

00:09:39.940 --> 00:09:44.850
And girls who grow up
with boys as brothers-- as

00:09:44.850 --> 00:09:47.045
opposed to plants as brothers.

00:09:47.045 --> 00:09:48.930
Whoa, what is happening here?

00:09:48.930 --> 00:09:53.270
OK, being a girl growing up
with brother brothers increases

00:09:53.270 --> 00:09:56.940
the likelihood of rough and
tumble play, because that's

00:09:56.940 --> 00:09:59.670
what you do with your
brother-- once again,

00:09:59.670 --> 00:10:01.670
uninterpretable literature.

00:10:01.670 --> 00:10:05.680
Generally, what you
see is very, very clear

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:10.060
cut androgenization of
aggressive behavior prenatal

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:13.000
testosterone when you're
looking at rodents.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.880
By the time you're looking at
primates, some pretty strong

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:18.540
patterns but nowhere near
as dramatic as in rodent

00:10:18.540 --> 00:10:19.750
species looked at.

00:10:19.750 --> 00:10:23.440
By the time you look at
humans, maybe just some hints,

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:25.310
but that at the most.

00:10:25.310 --> 00:10:27.520
Of the most interesting
realms, literatures,

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:30.580
where people have been thinking
about prenatal testosterone

00:10:30.580 --> 00:10:33.770
exposure is work
of a guy in the UK

00:10:33.770 --> 00:10:36.150
at Oxford named
Simon Baron-Cohen.

00:10:36.150 --> 00:10:40.580
And what he is, is basically
the world's expert on autism.

00:10:40.580 --> 00:10:44.190
And he has developed what
is called the hyper male

00:10:44.190 --> 00:10:46.790
hypothesis of autism.

00:10:46.790 --> 00:10:50.860
For starters, there's a
very, very big gender skew

00:10:50.860 --> 00:10:54.950
in autism-- far more frequent
among boys than girls,

00:10:54.950 --> 00:10:56.820
among males than females.

00:10:56.820 --> 00:11:00.760
And what Baron-Cohen has done
a lot of work on over the years

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:03.060
is first looking
at a whole array

00:11:03.060 --> 00:11:08.650
of sex differences between
normal human males and females.

00:11:08.650 --> 00:11:12.380
Sex differences, some of
it's the finger ratio stuff.

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:14.420
Some of it is
neural anatomy, some

00:11:14.420 --> 00:11:17.072
of those structural
differences in the brain,

00:11:17.072 --> 00:11:18.030
having to do with that.

00:11:18.030 --> 00:11:23.000
Some of it is functional spatial
skills versus language skills.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.450
Some of it is problem solving.

00:11:25.450 --> 00:11:28.990
And there is a gender
difference that

00:11:28.990 --> 00:11:33.210
tends to come through with that
on the average in that boys,

00:11:33.210 --> 00:11:36.680
males, men, take more
analytical approaches

00:11:36.680 --> 00:11:38.460
to social problem solving.

00:11:38.460 --> 00:11:42.600
Girls, women, females,
take more empathic ones.

00:11:42.600 --> 00:11:44.790
So that's a difference.

00:11:44.790 --> 00:11:46.760
OK, so he studied
all sorts of stuff

00:11:46.760 --> 00:11:48.920
like that, and obviously
with hormones as well--

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:52.580
all sorts of really subtle
interesting physical

00:11:52.580 --> 00:11:55.310
differences, whole
array of these.

00:11:55.310 --> 00:11:59.030
And what he has shown is
that individuals with autism,

00:11:59.030 --> 00:12:01.650
regardless of their
sex, tend to have

00:12:01.650 --> 00:12:04.570
even more exaggerated
versions of

00:12:04.570 --> 00:12:08.240
those male typical
profiles-- the finger length,

00:12:08.240 --> 00:12:12.680
the analytical focus at
the cost of social empathy,

00:12:12.680 --> 00:12:16.950
social affiliation, the
very strong spatial skills,

00:12:16.950 --> 00:12:18.400
whole bunch of those.

00:12:18.400 --> 00:12:20.730
So he's made a fairly
convincing argument,

00:12:20.730 --> 00:12:22.490
I think, that is good.

00:12:22.490 --> 00:12:26.070
Something's going on in terms
of prenatal androgenization,

00:12:26.070 --> 00:12:31.770
perhaps, which produces a more
masculinized profile, which

00:12:31.770 --> 00:12:34.960
taken to its extreme
winds up being autism.

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:36.810
In other words,
normal male behavior

00:12:36.810 --> 00:12:39.220
is just skating on
thin ice before going

00:12:39.220 --> 00:12:43.195
into this whole realm of sort
of dysfunctional socialization.

00:12:43.195 --> 00:12:44.730
Lots of stuff with
that, as we'll

00:12:44.730 --> 00:12:48.040
see next week some very
interesting differences

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:52.090
in the wiring of the cortex
of people with autism.

00:12:52.090 --> 00:12:56.340
And males show that same
thing, just not as extreme.

00:12:56.340 --> 00:12:59.910
OK, interesting footnote
thing-- Simon Baron-Cohen

00:12:59.910 --> 00:13:03.560
is apparently the cousin of
Sasha Baron-Cohen of Borat,

00:13:03.560 --> 00:13:07.140
which suggests that must be one
interesting family when they

00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:08.830
get together for the holidays.

00:13:08.830 --> 00:13:14.399
OK, moving back one
more box, however-- no,

00:13:14.399 --> 00:13:15.440
I'm not going to do that.

00:13:15.440 --> 00:13:17.120
OK, moving back one more box.

00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:20.320
Now, instead of
perinatal hormone stuff,

00:13:20.320 --> 00:13:22.860
early environment,
what about genes?

00:13:22.860 --> 00:13:23.640
What about genes?

00:13:23.640 --> 00:13:26.660
What do genes have to do
with aggression, competition,

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:28.540
cooperation, empathy, et cetera?

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:32.220
It used to be not that
long ago if you even raised

00:13:32.220 --> 00:13:36.260
the possibility that there were
genetic elements to aggression,

00:13:36.260 --> 00:13:39.030
you would be hounded
out of certain realms

00:13:39.030 --> 00:13:40.130
of social science.

00:13:40.130 --> 00:13:44.890
It was viewed as wildly
incorrect, wildly offensive,

00:13:44.890 --> 00:13:47.150
hidden agendas out the wazoo.

00:13:47.150 --> 00:13:51.600
For some reason, this began to
pass in the early '90s or so.

00:13:51.600 --> 00:13:54.490
There were studies in
the mid '80s, conferences

00:13:54.490 --> 00:13:57.100
in the mid '80s, where
there were protests.

00:13:57.100 --> 00:13:59.910
They were picketed, because
in this meeting that

00:13:59.910 --> 00:14:03.080
was considering the
sociology of aggression,

00:14:03.080 --> 00:14:04.910
the this of aggression,
the biology,

00:14:04.910 --> 00:14:07.000
the genetics, the
inclusion of it,

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.140
was the grounds
for the picketing.

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:11.920
A number of those were canceled
by the National Institutes

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:15.470
of Health under public pressure
of certain interest groups, all

00:14:15.470 --> 00:14:16.120
of that.

00:14:16.120 --> 00:14:19.430
It used to be viewed as
outrageously offensive,

00:14:19.430 --> 00:14:24.640
the notion that genes have
anything to do with aggression.

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:27.920
So there's two ways of
showing that that's wrong.

00:14:27.920 --> 00:14:30.020
The first is to
sit somebody down

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:33.190
and make them go through the
last 15 lectures in this class.

00:14:33.190 --> 00:14:35.990
Or the other is to
reflect on the fact

00:14:35.990 --> 00:14:38.170
that you would leave
a three-year-old

00:14:38.170 --> 00:14:41.850
in the care of a basset hound,
but not with a pit bull.

00:14:41.850 --> 00:14:47.000
Oh, there are breed-specific
differences in behavior.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.120
That, if nothing else,
is a demonstration of it,

00:14:50.120 --> 00:14:53.910
that dog breeds have been
bred for 20,000 years or so

00:14:53.910 --> 00:14:56.350
to differ in levels
of aggression,

00:14:56.350 --> 00:14:59.000
in levels of
affiliation, all of that.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:02.440
People who for some bizarre
reason follow bullfighting,

00:15:02.440 --> 00:15:06.180
there are lines of bulls,
different ranches of Spain

00:15:06.180 --> 00:15:08.370
in Mexico, where
they have been famous

00:15:08.370 --> 00:15:12.670
for centuries for the particular
fighting style of the bulls

00:15:12.670 --> 00:15:14.450
that they breed.

00:15:14.450 --> 00:15:15.940
Genes have something
to do with it.

00:15:15.940 --> 00:15:18.140
Of course they do,
because hormones

00:15:18.140 --> 00:15:19.400
have something to do with it.

00:15:19.400 --> 00:15:22.010
And because receptors,
and because enzymes,

00:15:22.010 --> 00:15:25.590
and everything with that, it
is impossible to have talked

00:15:25.590 --> 00:15:28.140
about any of this stuff on
the far right of the chart

00:15:28.140 --> 00:15:32.350
without invoking genes--
a ludicrous view.

00:15:32.350 --> 00:15:35.310
So what is known about
the relevance of genes

00:15:35.310 --> 00:15:38.080
to aspects of
aggressive behavior?

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:39.900
First off, at this
stage, there's

00:15:39.900 --> 00:15:42.910
been a whole bunch of studies--
many of them winding up

00:15:42.910 --> 00:15:45.810
in some very visible
journals-- where people find

00:15:45.810 --> 00:15:50.797
a gene implicating it in
abnormal levels of aggression,

00:15:50.797 --> 00:15:52.130
one of those sorts of behaviors.

00:15:52.130 --> 00:15:55.480
Typical strategy-- these might
be genetically engineered

00:15:55.480 --> 00:15:58.090
animals to remove that gene.

00:15:58.090 --> 00:16:00.640
Or there might be a
spontaneous mutation.

00:16:00.640 --> 00:16:03.020
And all of these
report that these

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:05.830
are animals with a whole
bunch of these mutations,

00:16:05.830 --> 00:16:07.750
that these are animals
with abnormally

00:16:07.750 --> 00:16:10.200
high levels of aggression.

00:16:10.200 --> 00:16:12.080
That's kind of a
clean experiment.

00:16:12.080 --> 00:16:15.900
If you go in-- and thanks to
a mutation, or chopping out

00:16:15.900 --> 00:16:18.190
one particular
gene, and now you've

00:16:18.190 --> 00:16:21.300
got a lot more aggression
in that individual.

00:16:21.300 --> 00:16:23.490
That kind of suggests
that that gene

00:16:23.490 --> 00:16:25.410
has something to do
with aggression, perhaps

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:26.870
a whole lot.

00:16:26.870 --> 00:16:29.460
What are all the
problems with that?

00:16:29.460 --> 00:16:31.260
Other ways that
that gene could be

00:16:31.260 --> 00:16:34.630
affecting behavior,
which indirectly winds up

00:16:34.630 --> 00:16:36.380
getting to aggression.

00:16:36.380 --> 00:16:39.440
One possibility-- what
if that's a gene that

00:16:39.440 --> 00:16:42.570
is relevant to impulsivity?

00:16:42.570 --> 00:16:45.340
And this is an
individual who, if you

00:16:45.340 --> 00:16:47.970
gave the mouse a
different realm of tests,

00:16:47.970 --> 00:16:52.880
would be shouting its love
to the world at an impusively

00:16:52.880 --> 00:16:55.050
high rate, just as
it's being aggressive

00:16:55.050 --> 00:16:56.910
at an impulsively high rate.

00:16:56.910 --> 00:17:01.080
Maybe it's a gene having
to do with impulsivity.

00:17:01.080 --> 00:17:04.579
Maybe it's a gene having to
do with one of the things

00:17:04.579 --> 00:17:05.800
we heard in the last lecture.

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:08.640
What are the environmental
releasing stimuli

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:09.980
that cause aggression to occur?

00:17:09.980 --> 00:17:11.650
What's one of the
most reliable ones?

00:17:11.650 --> 00:17:13.150
Pain.

00:17:13.150 --> 00:17:16.329
Oh, it turned out a
number of these strains

00:17:16.329 --> 00:17:19.240
of mice that were identified
with a gene knock-out.

00:17:19.240 --> 00:17:22.520
That here's a gene which
can cause aggression.

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:24.589
It turned out that
these were genes

00:17:24.589 --> 00:17:27.710
that made animals that were
much more sensitive to pain.

00:17:27.710 --> 00:17:30.380
And they were more
likely in a pain state

00:17:30.380 --> 00:17:34.200
to displace aggression
on to something else.

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:36.120
Or, as was shown
in some of these,

00:17:36.120 --> 00:17:38.150
these were animals who
were more aggressive.

00:17:38.150 --> 00:17:40.120
But they were also
more affiliative.

00:17:40.120 --> 00:17:43.640
And they were more everything.

00:17:43.640 --> 00:17:47.020
Their generic level of
arousal was a lot higher.

00:17:47.020 --> 00:17:50.160
So all these caveats, an
awful lot of the genes

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:53.010
that popped up in the first
generation of those sorts

00:17:53.010 --> 00:17:56.230
of studies that looked
solid, that were replicated,

00:17:56.230 --> 00:17:59.810
a lot of them instead had
to do with indirect routes,

00:17:59.810 --> 00:18:02.940
rather than directly
with aggression itself.

00:18:02.940 --> 00:18:05.640
So what about the genes
that have held up?

00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:08.640
And in the really
plausible candidate ones,

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:10.723
we've covered some of
these are already--

00:18:10.723 --> 00:18:15.780
the serotonin synthesis genes,
and the serotonin receptor

00:18:15.780 --> 00:18:17.740
genes, and the dopamine
receptor genes.

00:18:17.740 --> 00:18:21.580
All of those have been very
solidly implicated, really

00:18:21.580 --> 00:18:24.770
careful research, the
molecular biologists teaming up

00:18:24.770 --> 00:18:26.510
with behaviorists
knew what they were

00:18:26.510 --> 00:18:29.120
doing-- a genetic component.

00:18:29.120 --> 00:18:31.940
And what you know by now
that is absolutely about

00:18:31.940 --> 00:18:35.150
is this figure again.

00:18:35.150 --> 00:18:37.170
That's the case with
all of these genes.

00:18:37.170 --> 00:18:40.520
Oh my God, it's not
genes causing aggression.

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:42.730
We know exactly this
one, modulation,

00:18:42.730 --> 00:18:46.060
all that stuff, again
depending on the environment.

00:18:46.060 --> 00:18:49.090
And the environment
in the realm of genes

00:18:49.090 --> 00:18:50.970
relevant to aggression,
the environment

00:18:50.970 --> 00:18:55.890
is overwhelmingly about abuse
and stress early in life.

00:18:55.890 --> 00:18:59.850
So that's about as far as
genes will get you there,

00:18:59.850 --> 00:19:01.530
which is plenty
good, because this

00:19:01.530 --> 00:19:04.790
is exactly how the genes
should be relevant to behavior.

00:19:04.790 --> 00:19:07.880
This is how all genes
are relevant to behavior.

00:19:07.880 --> 00:19:11.110
Remember our ultimate punchline
from the behavior of genetics--

00:19:11.110 --> 00:19:12.590
at the end of the
day, it actually

00:19:12.590 --> 00:19:16.410
doesn't make any sense to
ever say what any gene does,

00:19:16.410 --> 00:19:18.320
only what it does
in the following

00:19:18.320 --> 00:19:20.680
range of environments.

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:24.000
In terms of that, what
you are beginning to find

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.780
is this still sort of
growing field which

00:19:27.780 --> 00:19:31.390
is beginning to look at
differences in these genotypes,

00:19:31.390 --> 00:19:33.910
these different
versions of these genes,

00:19:33.910 --> 00:19:37.460
in different populations,
in different cultures.

00:19:37.460 --> 00:19:40.330
And that's just beginning
as a literature.

00:19:40.330 --> 00:19:42.200
I'm not impressed
enough with the findings

00:19:42.200 --> 00:19:43.720
yet that it's worth
passing them on.

00:19:43.720 --> 00:19:47.680
But that is going to be
a very interesting field.

00:19:47.680 --> 00:19:51.020
Finally, there's always this
puzzle with any of these of,

00:19:51.020 --> 00:19:54.130
oh, you've got some gene
that's predisposing you

00:19:54.130 --> 00:19:57.340
towards being aggressive if
you were abused in childhood.

00:19:57.340 --> 00:20:01.280
We still know nothing
in terms of that gene.

00:20:01.280 --> 00:20:03.650
That gene has got
no predictive power

00:20:03.650 --> 00:20:07.330
as to whether this will thus
be someone who grows up and is

00:20:07.330 --> 00:20:09.030
a sociopathic murderer.

00:20:09.030 --> 00:20:13.240
Or if this is someone who grows
up and is just an unbelievably

00:20:13.240 --> 00:20:15.820
nasty Monopoly player.

00:20:15.820 --> 00:20:19.620
That factor, again,
that same deal-- oh,

00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:22.120
major frontal cortical
damage, disinhibition.

00:20:22.120 --> 00:20:24.130
You can't regulate
your behavior.

00:20:24.130 --> 00:20:27.590
No science in terms of
the neurobiology as to why

00:20:27.590 --> 00:20:30.260
one turns into a serial
murder, and the other one who

00:20:30.260 --> 00:20:33.210
doesn't catch clues that the
family wants to eat dinner.

00:20:33.210 --> 00:20:36.090
Again, it's the same
puzzle over and over.

00:20:36.090 --> 00:20:39.190
And, again, you could begin to
guess what the differences are

00:20:39.190 --> 00:20:40.400
going to be.

00:20:40.400 --> 00:20:43.710
Problems in some of these realms
with these aggressive genes,

00:20:43.710 --> 00:20:46.900
and different upbringings,
different stabilities

00:20:46.900 --> 00:20:49.570
and families, different
relationships, different role

00:20:49.570 --> 00:20:52.950
models, you can be off
and running with that one.

00:20:52.950 --> 00:20:56.090
One final domain in
genes and aggression--

00:20:56.090 --> 00:20:58.690
and only a handful of
you the other lecture

00:20:58.690 --> 00:21:00.330
knew who that guy
Charles Whitman

00:21:00.330 --> 00:21:02.400
was, who was the
guy who climbed up

00:21:02.400 --> 00:21:04.230
the Texas tower, all of that.

00:21:04.230 --> 00:21:07.000
OK, so here's another
chance to score points

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:09.100
in the mass murderer realm.

00:21:09.100 --> 00:21:11.720
How many people have ever heard
of a guy named Richard Speck?

00:21:14.816 --> 00:21:18.840
Wow, very few-- no hands.

00:21:18.840 --> 00:21:19.950
OK.

00:21:19.950 --> 00:21:22.850
No, that's a bottle
going up, not a hand.

00:21:22.850 --> 00:21:26.170
Richard Speck was once one
of the most notorious people

00:21:26.170 --> 00:21:27.180
in America.

00:21:27.180 --> 00:21:30.500
Richard Speck was a
nightmare sociopath

00:21:30.500 --> 00:21:34.780
who in 1968 committed
a crime that just

00:21:34.780 --> 00:21:37.130
stunned the entire country.

00:21:37.130 --> 00:21:39.410
People wrote songs about it.

00:21:39.410 --> 00:21:42.990
It was just as brutal
as one could imagine.

00:21:42.990 --> 00:21:47.420
He broke into the
apartment of eight nurses

00:21:47.420 --> 00:21:49.810
living in Chicago,
eight student nurses,

00:21:49.810 --> 00:21:51.950
and slaughtered them all.

00:21:51.950 --> 00:21:58.010
And this was shocking on a
level that's hard to describe.

00:21:58.010 --> 00:22:02.820
Richard Speck was the
nightmare sociopathic murderer.

00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:06.980
So he gets sent off to
prison eventually for life.

00:22:06.980 --> 00:22:09.860
And in the process at
some point or other,

00:22:09.860 --> 00:22:12.450
he's getting some physical exam.

00:22:12.450 --> 00:22:14.840
Somebody takes a blood
sample something.

00:22:14.840 --> 00:22:17.290
And a lab technician
notices something

00:22:17.290 --> 00:22:19.920
interesting in his
blood, examining

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:24.350
the chareotypes, the
structures, of his chromosomes.

00:22:24.350 --> 00:22:27.780
And they discovered that
he had an extremely rare

00:22:27.780 --> 00:22:30.160
chromosomal abnormality.

00:22:30.160 --> 00:22:35.690
Females, XX, males,
XY-- every now

00:22:35.690 --> 00:22:38.140
and then you get somebody
where something screws up.

00:22:38.140 --> 00:22:41.270
And what you now get is XYY.

00:22:41.270 --> 00:22:43.760
You get an extra Y chromosome.

00:22:43.760 --> 00:22:46.670
And, suddenly, this had
to be the explanation

00:22:46.670 --> 00:22:47.780
for what was going on.

00:22:47.780 --> 00:22:50.600
Males are a total pain in
the ass all over the world.

00:22:50.600 --> 00:22:52.100
And they've got
those Y chromosomes.

00:22:52.100 --> 00:22:52.680
Oh my God.

00:22:52.680 --> 00:22:55.850
The guy has two Y chromosomes
in every single cell.

00:22:55.850 --> 00:22:56.730
This explains it.

00:22:56.730 --> 00:22:59.670
And this suddenly
started this hysteria

00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:02.840
about violence and the XYY male.

00:23:02.840 --> 00:23:05.620
Senators were
bellowing in Congress

00:23:05.620 --> 00:23:09.420
about how we needed to screen
our schoolteachers to make

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:12.440
sure none of the men
had XYY profiles.

00:23:12.440 --> 00:23:16.410
The military was all set to
start testing recruits for XYY.

00:23:16.410 --> 00:23:18.800
Although it's not clear if
that would get you in or would

00:23:18.800 --> 00:23:21.020
that get you out,
how that one worked.

00:23:21.020 --> 00:23:22.610
But they were
suddenly interested.

00:23:22.610 --> 00:23:25.200
Tons of work went
into it, this flurry

00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:27.120
of excitement, special funding.

00:23:27.120 --> 00:23:28.900
We need to be on top of this.

00:23:28.900 --> 00:23:31.150
And by the early '70s,
what was clear was

00:23:31.150 --> 00:23:33.460
there was no
relationship whatsoever.

00:23:33.460 --> 00:23:35.080
So that one went down the tubes.

00:23:35.080 --> 00:23:37.390
And then one of those
ironic ending departments,

00:23:37.390 --> 00:23:40.990
it was eventually discovered
that a lab technician had

00:23:40.990 --> 00:23:43.680
blown, had done the
chareotyping wrong.

00:23:43.680 --> 00:23:46.340
And he really
wasn't an XYY male,

00:23:46.340 --> 00:23:49.150
despite that lab technician
then having called up

00:23:49.150 --> 00:23:50.080
the newspapers.

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:53.500
He was a normal XY
sociopathic male.

00:23:53.500 --> 00:23:56.870
So that one was up
there for a while,

00:23:56.870 --> 00:24:01.800
more realms of don't overvalue
the genetic evidence.

00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:05.060
So that shifts us now
one step further back.

00:24:05.060 --> 00:24:08.690
And now begin to look
at whole populations--

00:24:08.690 --> 00:24:12.050
whole populations not yet on
the genetic evolutionary level.

00:24:12.050 --> 00:24:14.810
But what do things
like ecology have

00:24:14.810 --> 00:24:16.940
to do with levels of aggression?

00:24:16.940 --> 00:24:19.313
What does culture
have to do with it?

00:24:19.313 --> 00:24:21.500
What does factors like that?

00:24:21.500 --> 00:24:26.240
And there's a really interesting
array of findings out there.

00:24:26.240 --> 00:24:28.870
First off, one
important dichotomy

00:24:28.870 --> 00:24:31.390
when looking at
traditional human cultures

00:24:31.390 --> 00:24:34.280
is how people make their living.

00:24:34.280 --> 00:24:35.900
And the one that's
pertinent here

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:39.500
is the dichotomy between
pastoralist people

00:24:39.500 --> 00:24:40.910
and everybody else.

00:24:40.910 --> 00:24:44.590
Pastoralist people, nomadic
pastoralists people, these

00:24:44.590 --> 00:24:45.800
are cow people.

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:48.390
These are people who wander
around with their goats,

00:24:48.390 --> 00:24:49.750
or their camels.

00:24:49.750 --> 00:24:52.170
These are the
shepherds, in contrast

00:24:52.170 --> 00:24:56.610
to traditional
agriculturalists, or far rarer

00:24:56.610 --> 00:24:59.870
traditional hunter-gatherers--
so nomadic pastoralists

00:24:59.870 --> 00:25:01.490
versus everyone else.

00:25:01.490 --> 00:25:04.850
And what a boatload of
anthropology has shown

00:25:04.850 --> 00:25:09.770
is nomadic pastoralists have
higher rates of violence

00:25:09.770 --> 00:25:13.080
both within group
and between group.

00:25:13.080 --> 00:25:17.520
Nomadic pastoralists are vastly
more likely than other groups

00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:23.140
to have standing
armies, warrior classes,

00:25:23.140 --> 00:25:25.980
to have leadership be
derived from people

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:29.570
who have had the most
success as a warrior,

00:25:29.570 --> 00:25:33.680
to have myths built around their
religion that success in war,

00:25:33.680 --> 00:25:37.490
violent acclaim in war,
is your gateway to heaven,

00:25:37.490 --> 00:25:40.610
or whatever afterlife is
viewed as most desirable.

00:25:40.610 --> 00:25:42.430
This is a consistent finding.

00:25:42.430 --> 00:25:46.060
Lots and lots of these
cultures, nomadic pastoralists

00:25:46.060 --> 00:25:50.360
are the ones who came up with
warfare on a certain level,

00:25:50.360 --> 00:25:51.820
and warrior classes.

00:25:51.820 --> 00:25:54.110
And this makes perfect
sense, because one feature

00:25:54.110 --> 00:25:57.130
of being a nomadic
pastoralist is you're nomadic.

00:25:57.130 --> 00:25:59.730
At certain times of
the year, there's

00:25:59.730 --> 00:26:03.370
one subset of the whole
village who's off 15 miles

00:26:03.370 --> 00:26:05.350
away where there's
some good grazing.

00:26:05.350 --> 00:26:07.130
Another group is
on the other side.

00:26:07.130 --> 00:26:10.050
And what this sets you up for
is something that farmers never

00:26:10.050 --> 00:26:11.300
have to worry about.

00:26:11.300 --> 00:26:14.900
Somebody can't come and rustle
your farm away at night.

00:26:14.900 --> 00:26:17.800
But people can come and
steal all your animals.

00:26:17.800 --> 00:26:20.960
Warrior classes, so
that at any given point,

00:26:20.960 --> 00:26:24.910
if people are dispersed, there
is still a designated age group

00:26:24.910 --> 00:26:29.250
of individuals who are out there
to defend the collective herds

00:26:29.250 --> 00:26:30.530
of the group.

00:26:30.530 --> 00:26:32.030
So you see that.

00:26:32.030 --> 00:26:34.270
In the United States,
where that has had

00:26:34.270 --> 00:26:37.270
an interesting
manifestation is where

00:26:37.270 --> 00:26:40.350
people settled in the
original 13 colonies,

00:26:40.350 --> 00:26:42.510
from which part of
the United Kingdom.

00:26:42.510 --> 00:26:45.930
And some very influential
studies, really interesting

00:26:45.930 --> 00:26:49.750
creative ones, pointing
out that the American South

00:26:49.750 --> 00:26:53.050
was disproportionately
settled by sheep people

00:26:53.050 --> 00:26:56.330
from the northern ends
of the British Isles--

00:26:56.330 --> 00:26:58.920
in other words,
nomadic pastoralists.

00:26:58.920 --> 00:27:02.820
Shifting to another realm of
anthropological designation,

00:27:02.820 --> 00:27:06.510
these are people who
disproportionately have

00:27:06.510 --> 00:27:09.520
come from cultures of honor.

00:27:09.520 --> 00:27:12.940
Cultures of honor,
where people are

00:27:12.940 --> 00:27:17.290
willing to kill over very
symbolic slights rather

00:27:17.290 --> 00:27:20.420
than over material
conflicts, where there

00:27:20.420 --> 00:27:22.570
are vendettas within
the group, there

00:27:22.570 --> 00:27:24.980
are vendettas
between groups, where

00:27:24.980 --> 00:27:27.970
it is honorific
to have to avenge

00:27:27.970 --> 00:27:29.780
a death, which you
do not necessarily

00:27:29.780 --> 00:27:32.620
find in agriculturalists.

00:27:32.620 --> 00:27:35.880
Cultures of honor, and
that goes hand-in-hand

00:27:35.880 --> 00:27:37.430
with nomadic pastoralism.

00:27:37.430 --> 00:27:39.510
And what you get
there, typically,

00:27:39.510 --> 00:27:44.400
are very clear rules
about enforced hospitality

00:27:44.400 --> 00:27:49.860
for guests, and very clear
rules of the circumstances

00:27:49.860 --> 00:27:54.430
of aggression, retributive
ones, over symbolic affronts.

00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:58.040
And that's really clear
difference regionally

00:27:58.040 --> 00:27:59.670
in this country.

00:27:59.670 --> 00:28:02.010
Interesting sociologist,
University of Michigan,

00:28:02.010 --> 00:28:04.020
named Richard Nesbett.

00:28:04.020 --> 00:28:05.490
And he grew up in the South.

00:28:05.490 --> 00:28:07.360
And I actually heard
him once give a talk

00:28:07.360 --> 00:28:10.870
where he talks about how
when he was about 18 or so,

00:28:10.870 --> 00:28:12.910
he left the South
for the first time

00:28:12.910 --> 00:28:16.090
and joined this very
strange culture at Harvard

00:28:16.090 --> 00:28:17.850
University as an undergraduate.

00:28:17.850 --> 00:28:22.500
And he was dumbfounded by how
different of a world this was.

00:28:22.500 --> 00:28:25.630
People didn't shoot
relatives at picnics,

00:28:25.630 --> 00:28:29.110
at barbecues, which
sounded totally facetious.

00:28:29.110 --> 00:28:31.530
But when you look
at the higher crime

00:28:31.530 --> 00:28:34.620
rates in the American
South, it is not

00:28:34.620 --> 00:28:36.620
occurring in urban areas.

00:28:36.620 --> 00:28:39.390
Urban crime is
roughly equivalent

00:28:39.390 --> 00:28:40.960
all throughout
the United States.

00:28:40.960 --> 00:28:43.910
It is not due to
higher rates of what

00:28:43.910 --> 00:28:47.970
they call 7-Eleven robberies,
which is just material

00:28:47.970 --> 00:28:49.940
gain, a robbery of that sort.

00:28:49.940 --> 00:28:52.010
It is murders of honor.

00:28:52.010 --> 00:28:55.520
It is people who know each
other at social settings,

00:28:55.520 --> 00:28:59.760
people who have some insult,
have something that has nothing

00:28:59.760 --> 00:29:01.660
to do with material wealth.

00:29:01.660 --> 00:29:04.330
This is where the
disproportionate violence comes

00:29:04.330 --> 00:29:06.640
from in the American South.

00:29:06.640 --> 00:29:08.750
And prompted by
that, Nesbett did

00:29:08.750 --> 00:29:12.810
one of the all-time interesting
studies, this famous, amazing

00:29:12.810 --> 00:29:13.510
study.

00:29:13.510 --> 00:29:15.590
So he's at the
University of Michigan.

00:29:15.590 --> 00:29:18.630
And he recruits
student volunteers

00:29:18.630 --> 00:29:25.630
who believe they're going
in to do a hopscotch test,

00:29:25.630 --> 00:29:26.566
or some such thing.

00:29:26.566 --> 00:29:27.440
And they're going in.

00:29:27.440 --> 00:29:29.970
But he made a point of finding
out where everyone came from.

00:29:29.970 --> 00:29:32.620
And he got a fairly
even distribution

00:29:32.620 --> 00:29:35.000
between the relatively
few students in Michigan

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.380
from the American
South, and then students

00:29:37.380 --> 00:29:39.210
from the more traditional North.

00:29:39.210 --> 00:29:42.300
So we get into the psych
building, each individual who's

00:29:42.300 --> 00:29:44.100
coming for their appointment.

00:29:44.100 --> 00:29:45.351
And they take the elevator.

00:29:45.351 --> 00:29:46.100
And they come out.

00:29:46.100 --> 00:29:47.610
And they walk down the hall.

00:29:47.610 --> 00:29:50.440
And this is where the
experiment happens.

00:29:50.440 --> 00:29:53.190
Nesbett has somebody
working on the project--

00:29:53.190 --> 00:29:59.530
a confederate on the project,
I say making a lame pun, OK.

00:29:59.530 --> 00:30:01.652
So a confederate on
the project, a person

00:30:01.652 --> 00:30:02.610
working on the project.

00:30:02.610 --> 00:30:06.160
And this was a big, beefy guy.

00:30:06.160 --> 00:30:09.600
And the whole idea was
that this big, beefy guy

00:30:09.600 --> 00:30:11.790
was going to do
something insulting

00:30:11.790 --> 00:30:15.765
to this individual walking
down the hallway, all male.

00:30:15.765 --> 00:30:16.640
Here's what they did.

00:30:16.640 --> 00:30:19.250
They clearly did
a lot of thinking

00:30:19.250 --> 00:30:22.560
in designing this study, in
terms of what single word

00:30:22.560 --> 00:30:24.270
this person was going to say.

00:30:24.270 --> 00:30:26.560
And this is what
he wound up saying.

00:30:26.560 --> 00:30:28.700
The volunteer would be
walking down the hall.

00:30:28.700 --> 00:30:31.720
Here comes this big,
beefy guy moving fast.

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:34.850
And as he comes by him, bumps
into him with his shoulder,

00:30:34.850 --> 00:30:39.710
walks past, and says, watch it,
asshole, and then disappears.

00:30:39.710 --> 00:30:42.020
Volunteer comes in
to start their study,

00:30:42.020 --> 00:30:45.620
and quickly they look at blood
pressure, and heart rate,

00:30:45.620 --> 00:30:48.430
and stress hormone levels,
and testosterone levels,

00:30:48.430 --> 00:30:52.370
and get a typical participant
in this study from the North.

00:30:52.370 --> 00:30:53.360
And they come in.

00:30:53.360 --> 00:30:55.670
And they're a little bit
irritated, and what a jerk,

00:30:55.670 --> 00:30:56.336
and all of that.

00:30:56.336 --> 00:30:58.240
And it's all over with
two minutes later.

00:30:58.240 --> 00:30:59.820
Get people from
the American South,

00:30:59.820 --> 00:31:03.560
on the average massive stress
response, hypertension,

00:31:03.560 --> 00:31:07.510
elevated testosterone levels,
big regional differences.

00:31:07.510 --> 00:31:09.770
These are some of the
physiological pictures

00:31:09.770 --> 00:31:13.010
of cultures of honor.

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:13.860
What else?

00:31:13.860 --> 00:31:17.790
What other interesting things
about ecosystems, or ecology,

00:31:17.790 --> 00:31:19.050
or cultural aspects?

00:31:19.050 --> 00:31:23.020
Another dichotomy that is
really consistent-- and this one

00:31:23.020 --> 00:31:26.290
maps pretty readily on that
pastoralist versus everybody

00:31:26.290 --> 00:31:30.470
else-- the sorts of cultures
and the level of violence

00:31:30.470 --> 00:31:32.930
that are generated
in cultures that live

00:31:32.930 --> 00:31:36.840
in deserts versus rain forests.

00:31:36.840 --> 00:31:39.500
And, once again,
deserts are where

00:31:39.500 --> 00:31:43.080
you are far more likely to
find nomadic pastoralists, rain

00:31:43.080 --> 00:31:46.660
forests, hunter-gatherers,
mixture of hunter-gatherers,

00:31:46.660 --> 00:31:49.960
small farm agriculturists--
two totally different worlds

00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:51.100
of occupations.

00:31:51.100 --> 00:31:53.720
And what you see
is far higher rates

00:31:53.720 --> 00:31:56.360
of violence within
group and between groups

00:31:56.360 --> 00:31:57.860
in desert dwellers.

00:31:57.860 --> 00:32:02.230
And that maps very
logically onto pastoralists

00:32:02.230 --> 00:32:03.840
versus everybody else.

00:32:03.840 --> 00:32:06.950
Desert dwellers, open
savanna grasslands,

00:32:06.950 --> 00:32:09.520
that's where you see
the warrior classes.

00:32:09.520 --> 00:32:12.010
That's where you see
raiding of other tribes.

00:32:12.010 --> 00:32:15.120
That's where you get that
pattern, virtually none

00:32:15.120 --> 00:32:17.420
among the hunter-gatherers.

00:32:17.420 --> 00:32:19.020
I might point out
something which

00:32:19.020 --> 00:32:21.910
will become sort of focused
on more in a lecture in about

00:32:21.910 --> 00:32:23.540
a week or so.

00:32:23.540 --> 00:32:28.490
I should point out that desert
dweller nomadic pastoralists

00:32:28.490 --> 00:32:30.450
are also the cultures
on this planet that

00:32:30.450 --> 00:32:33.110
invented monotheism.

00:32:33.110 --> 00:32:35.880
Consistent difference--
desert dwellers

00:32:35.880 --> 00:32:37.550
tend more towards monotheism.

00:32:37.550 --> 00:32:40.660
And it was invented by
desert nomadic pastoralists.

00:32:40.660 --> 00:32:43.640
Rainforest cultures
far disproportionately

00:32:43.640 --> 00:32:45.700
tend to be polytheistic.

00:32:45.700 --> 00:32:47.620
And this is not
remotely surprising.

00:32:47.620 --> 00:32:49.560
If you're living in a
rainforest and there's

00:32:49.560 --> 00:32:52.707
10,000 different types of
edible plants around there,

00:32:52.707 --> 00:32:55.040
it doesn't take a lot of work
to come up with the notion

00:32:55.040 --> 00:32:58.850
that there's lots of different
spirits and gods out there.

00:32:58.850 --> 00:33:03.580
What the desert it is about is
one, singular baked truth there

00:33:03.580 --> 00:33:04.930
of surviving.

00:33:04.930 --> 00:33:07.070
That's where
monotheism was born.

00:33:07.070 --> 00:33:08.980
Monotheism,
historically, is more

00:33:08.980 --> 00:33:12.850
associated with cultures that
invented warfare, and invented

00:33:12.850 --> 00:33:16.750
warrior classes, and raiding,
and things of that sort.

00:33:16.750 --> 00:33:19.030
That's kind of interesting.

00:33:19.030 --> 00:33:23.450
OK, moving on, more cultural
differences-- one of the great,

00:33:23.450 --> 00:33:28.840
great predictors of having a
society with lots of violence

00:33:28.840 --> 00:33:31.250
in it, and lots of
warfare elsewhere,

00:33:31.250 --> 00:33:35.370
is a culture that has
rots of cultural myths

00:33:35.370 --> 00:33:37.180
of victimization.

00:33:37.180 --> 00:33:40.690
We have been screwed
historically, because of this,

00:33:40.690 --> 00:33:45.060
this, and this, and coupled
with that an ethos of not

00:33:45.060 --> 00:33:48.520
turning the other cheek,
but instead of retribution.

00:33:48.520 --> 00:33:52.360
Cultures that have
strong histories

00:33:52.360 --> 00:33:55.850
and or myths of victimization,
and strong values

00:33:55.850 --> 00:33:59.930
built around retribution are
extremely violent societies,

00:33:59.930 --> 00:34:03.580
and often really bad
news as neighbors.

00:34:03.580 --> 00:34:05.030
What else?

00:34:05.030 --> 00:34:07.660
Amazing study that got
published about a year ago,

00:34:07.660 --> 00:34:10.460
which is on the
recommended reading list.

00:34:10.460 --> 00:34:11.679
This is not required.

00:34:11.679 --> 00:34:14.710
But this was a deeply
interesting study.

00:34:14.710 --> 00:34:15.210
It

00:34:15.210 --> 00:34:17.110
Was one of those
game theory studies.

00:34:17.110 --> 00:34:18.980
It was a game a little
bit like prisoner's

00:34:18.980 --> 00:34:22.800
dilemma-- not exactly the same,
but the same sort of notions

00:34:22.800 --> 00:34:26.350
that you could be very generous
in your game playing style.

00:34:26.350 --> 00:34:28.310
You could be absolutely
rationally fair.

00:34:28.310 --> 00:34:31.639
You could be exploited, a
whole range of possibilities.

00:34:31.639 --> 00:34:33.500
What these guys
did in this study

00:34:33.500 --> 00:34:38.750
was take scads of people
from 40 different countries.

00:34:38.750 --> 00:34:41.210
No they didn't,
from 16, 19, they

00:34:41.210 --> 00:34:44.940
took from a bunch of
different countries.

00:34:44.940 --> 00:34:47.590
And just to control for
things, all of the subjects

00:34:47.590 --> 00:34:49.170
were university students.

00:34:49.170 --> 00:34:52.380
So you're selecting for a
fairly homogeneous bunch,

00:34:52.380 --> 00:34:55.459
both within group and across
these different countries.

00:34:55.459 --> 00:34:59.200
And what they did was they
had people play these games.

00:34:59.200 --> 00:35:03.630
And they had the option for what
is called altruistic punishing,

00:35:03.630 --> 00:35:07.340
which we will hear more about
in a little while, which is you

00:35:07.340 --> 00:35:11.290
have the option to expend
some of your resources--

00:35:11.290 --> 00:35:13.560
your points, your
chips, whatever--

00:35:13.560 --> 00:35:18.269
you can spend to punish the
other individual for cheating.

00:35:18.269 --> 00:35:19.810
And the question,
of course, becomes,

00:35:19.810 --> 00:35:22.576
how much are you willing
to spend to punish somebody

00:35:22.576 --> 00:35:24.200
when they've been
cheating against you,

00:35:24.200 --> 00:35:26.780
when they've been stingy, when
they haven't reciprocated,

00:35:26.780 --> 00:35:28.040
all of that?

00:35:28.040 --> 00:35:30.930
First finding,
which is everybody

00:35:30.930 --> 00:35:32.820
across all the
countries averaged out

00:35:32.820 --> 00:35:35.660
to the same rate, the
percentage of resources

00:35:35.660 --> 00:35:37.340
that someone is
willing to expend

00:35:37.340 --> 00:35:41.410
on punishing a cheater-- so no
particular cultural differences

00:35:41.410 --> 00:35:42.222
there.

00:35:42.222 --> 00:35:46.180
But then they identified
another interesting realm

00:35:46.180 --> 00:35:49.790
of game behavior here,
which they called antisocial

00:35:49.790 --> 00:35:52.650
punishment, which
is where it's not

00:35:52.650 --> 00:35:55.770
that you are expending some
of your resources to punish

00:35:55.770 --> 00:35:57.280
somebody for having cheated.

00:35:57.280 --> 00:35:59.440
It's where you're
expending resources

00:35:59.440 --> 00:36:04.070
to punish someone for
having been overly generous.

00:36:04.070 --> 00:36:07.210
And that pops up in
certain sorts of games.

00:36:07.210 --> 00:36:09.240
It is not terribly
common when it's

00:36:09.240 --> 00:36:12.140
the person who is choosing
with their opponent.

00:36:12.140 --> 00:36:14.520
But when you have
a third party, you

00:36:14.520 --> 00:36:17.210
have no cultural differences
at the rate at which they

00:36:17.210 --> 00:36:18.940
are willing to punish cheaters.

00:36:18.940 --> 00:36:21.270
But here's where
the differences came

00:36:21.270 --> 00:36:24.720
then, the rate at which
people would punish

00:36:24.720 --> 00:36:27.330
unexpectedly generous players.

00:36:27.330 --> 00:36:29.320
And you got a big spread.

00:36:29.320 --> 00:36:31.630
The lowest rate at
which this happened

00:36:31.630 --> 00:36:34.930
was, nicely, as it
turned out, people

00:36:34.930 --> 00:36:37.840
from this country, which is kind
of nice, people from England.

00:36:37.840 --> 00:36:39.790
And, of course, who else?

00:36:39.790 --> 00:36:44.450
The ever-useful Scandinavians
with their powerhouses

00:36:44.450 --> 00:36:47.510
of the cells and their
other cliches all set.

00:36:47.510 --> 00:36:49.820
So the Scandinavians
come through yet again.

00:36:49.820 --> 00:36:51.870
But, for once, we're able
to hang out with them

00:36:51.870 --> 00:36:54.230
and actually count as
having a good profile--

00:36:54.230 --> 00:36:57.390
the lowest rates of
people being willing to do

00:36:57.390 --> 00:37:02.040
this nutso anti-social
punishing in those countries.

00:37:02.040 --> 00:37:05.580
In between rates-- a number
of Middle Eastern countries,

00:37:05.580 --> 00:37:10.060
a large number of Eastern
Bloc countries, in other words

00:37:10.060 --> 00:37:13.712
Slavic ones that used to be
part of the Soviet Union, Korea,

00:37:13.712 --> 00:37:15.220
and turkey.

00:37:15.220 --> 00:37:16.630
Those were the middle ones.

00:37:16.630 --> 00:37:18.580
Which ones had the worst rates?

00:37:18.580 --> 00:37:20.520
I will just read the
two countries here

00:37:20.520 --> 00:37:23.520
that were way up there,
a big gap between them

00:37:23.520 --> 00:37:24.770
and the rest of the countries.

00:37:24.770 --> 00:37:27.210
One was Greece.

00:37:27.210 --> 00:37:32.810
And the other were the Arabic
Emirates on the Saudi Arabian

00:37:32.810 --> 00:37:37.840
Peninsula, where people
are willing to spend more

00:37:37.840 --> 00:37:41.000
to do anti-social
punishing than they

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:43.830
are willing to spend
to punish cheaters,

00:37:43.830 --> 00:37:45.910
extraordinary finding.

00:37:45.910 --> 00:37:49.660
People from Muscat, which
was where the university was,

00:37:49.660 --> 00:37:53.210
those students were more
willing to punish someone

00:37:53.210 --> 00:37:56.570
for being unexpectedly
generous than for somebody

00:37:56.570 --> 00:38:02.200
cheating on a game theory social
contract-- totally amazing.

00:38:02.200 --> 00:38:03.290
So what's that about?

00:38:03.290 --> 00:38:05.080
When they actually
question people,

00:38:05.080 --> 00:38:06.870
you see things with
people from there

00:38:06.870 --> 00:38:09.300
along the lines
of, if people start

00:38:09.300 --> 00:38:11.750
doing that, of being
all generous like that,

00:38:11.750 --> 00:38:13.970
it's just going to up
the ante for everybody.

00:38:13.970 --> 00:38:16.520
Everybody's going to
have to start doing that.

00:38:16.520 --> 00:38:18.370
That's an interesting
piece of reasoning.

00:38:18.370 --> 00:38:21.220
But when you look at a larger
level, what these researchers

00:38:21.220 --> 00:38:23.790
then showed was a
predictor across all

00:38:23.790 --> 00:38:25.620
these different
societies of the rate

00:38:25.620 --> 00:38:30.340
of this anti-social punishment
levels of trust in the society.

00:38:30.340 --> 00:38:33.170
Some standard metrics
used by sociologists

00:38:33.170 --> 00:38:37.110
who were interested in this
concept of social capital--

00:38:37.110 --> 00:38:40.610
how much social trust there
is in the society, how

00:38:40.610 --> 00:38:44.230
much participation there is,
how much of a sense of efficacy.

00:38:44.230 --> 00:38:46.630
And what you see is
the lower the levels

00:38:46.630 --> 00:38:49.290
of social capital
in these societies,

00:38:49.290 --> 00:38:52.990
the higher the rates of this
anti-social punishment, totally

00:38:52.990 --> 00:38:55.040
interesting study.

00:38:55.040 --> 00:38:57.580
Next in the realm
of culture, what

00:38:57.580 --> 00:38:59.980
are people doing
these days, what

00:38:59.980 --> 00:39:02.420
is sort of the science and
the research these days,

00:39:02.420 --> 00:39:05.270
trying to make
sense of terrorism,

00:39:05.270 --> 00:39:07.650
and the sort of cultures
that give rise to them,

00:39:07.650 --> 00:39:10.760
and the sort of ideologies
that give rise to them?

00:39:10.760 --> 00:39:13.400
A number of basic
dichotomies-- one

00:39:13.400 --> 00:39:16.130
is a camp that
views it as always

00:39:16.130 --> 00:39:18.840
abnormal sociopathic behavior.

00:39:18.840 --> 00:39:21.250
Another is a camp that
just views terrorism

00:39:21.250 --> 00:39:24.080
as extremes of ideology.

00:39:24.080 --> 00:39:27.920
The first one is much more
about individual dysfunction--

00:39:27.920 --> 00:39:31.040
oh, this is a neuropsychiatric
problem, perhaps.

00:39:31.040 --> 00:39:33.620
The second one is
one more a feature

00:39:33.620 --> 00:39:36.820
of cultures that have
extremely strong ideologies.

00:39:36.820 --> 00:39:39.720
So that's one division in
there as to how to think

00:39:39.720 --> 00:39:41.320
about it in the community.

00:39:41.320 --> 00:39:44.040
Another division is
really interesting.

00:39:44.040 --> 00:39:46.550
And it's one my reading
of this literature

00:39:46.550 --> 00:39:49.580
that has totally thrown people
in the field for a loop.

00:39:49.580 --> 00:39:52.870
Forever, there has
been a profile,

00:39:52.870 --> 00:39:55.290
a demographic and
psychological profile,

00:39:55.290 --> 00:39:57.550
of individuals who
are terrorists,

00:39:57.550 --> 00:40:00.300
all the way back to the
people who did the Boston Tea

00:40:00.300 --> 00:40:02.920
Party in this country, the IRA.

00:40:02.920 --> 00:40:05.840
All sorts of stuff like
that, the Haganah, which

00:40:05.840 --> 00:40:09.440
was in Israel, terrorist
acts before independence,

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:11.420
studied in a whole
bunch of these

00:40:11.420 --> 00:40:14.570
that there tends to be a
rather consistent profile

00:40:14.570 --> 00:40:17.190
of these individuals
who would be terrorists.

00:40:17.190 --> 00:40:26.030
Young, male, socially isolated,
socially unaffiliated in terms

00:40:26.030 --> 00:40:31.930
of relationships, relatively
uneducated background,

00:40:31.930 --> 00:40:39.710
history of childhood abuse, and
another factor which has just

00:40:39.710 --> 00:40:43.410
completely slipped my mind.

00:40:43.410 --> 00:40:46.230
What was it?

00:40:46.230 --> 00:40:47.200
Oh you all know.

00:40:47.200 --> 00:40:49.620
OK, so that's exactly what
you find in these folks--

00:40:49.620 --> 00:40:53.830
a picture of isolated
sociopathic individuals

00:40:53.830 --> 00:40:57.150
who already have a history
of anti-social behavior.

00:40:57.150 --> 00:40:59.630
These are people who,
if they hadn't stumbled

00:40:59.630 --> 00:41:01.460
into this cause,
would be spending

00:41:01.460 --> 00:41:03.840
their time mugging old ladies.

00:41:03.840 --> 00:41:05.340
That would be that profile.

00:41:05.340 --> 00:41:07.630
And you look at
these various groups.

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:10.010
And that has been
a consistent one.

00:41:10.010 --> 00:41:13.540
Terrorism in the recent years,
particularly Middle Eastern

00:41:13.540 --> 00:41:17.120
fundamentalist, is a
completely different profile.

00:41:17.120 --> 00:41:19.440
It is not young men.

00:41:19.440 --> 00:41:22.680
It tends to be educated,
well-off people

00:41:22.680 --> 00:41:27.390
in their thirties and forties,
overwhelmingly middle class

00:41:27.390 --> 00:41:29.990
or upper class backgrounds.

00:41:29.990 --> 00:41:32.850
Next, it's not just
middle-aged males.

00:41:32.850 --> 00:41:34.180
It's females.

00:41:34.180 --> 00:41:36.860
It's women to a much
higher extent than seen

00:41:36.860 --> 00:41:39.430
in any previous
sort of population

00:41:39.430 --> 00:41:41.620
dealing with terrorism.

00:41:41.620 --> 00:41:45.030
Next what you see is
these are individuals

00:41:45.030 --> 00:41:47.860
who, on the average,
tend not to have

00:41:47.860 --> 00:41:52.500
had any direct exposure
to the suppression

00:41:52.500 --> 00:41:54.910
that they are fighting against.

00:41:54.910 --> 00:41:58.830
As opposed to the sociopathic
model, a classic picture

00:41:58.830 --> 00:42:03.180
with IRA gunman, the father
was taken away by the whoevers,

00:42:03.180 --> 00:42:05.150
shot, never came back again.

00:42:05.150 --> 00:42:07.420
And they were passed
on the family mantle.

00:42:07.420 --> 00:42:10.300
The current picture is
a very different oe--

00:42:10.300 --> 00:42:15.350
no direct experience
of the persecution.

00:42:15.350 --> 00:42:19.550
Finally, tending not to have
particularly high levels

00:42:19.550 --> 00:42:24.020
of religiosity, and this is
this very contemporary profile

00:42:24.020 --> 00:42:27.720
where you get these 40-year-old
engineers who are suicide

00:42:27.720 --> 00:42:29.850
bombers, where they go home.

00:42:29.850 --> 00:42:31.390
They say goodbye
to their families.

00:42:31.390 --> 00:42:34.730
They make a video tape sort
of wishing everybody well.

00:42:34.730 --> 00:42:37.250
And after having quit their
job and paying the rent one

00:42:37.250 --> 00:42:40.440
extra month, and off they
go and blow themselves up.

00:42:40.440 --> 00:42:43.190
People, I sense, in the
field haven't a clue

00:42:43.190 --> 00:42:46.880
how to make sense of what
this is about, very new,

00:42:46.880 --> 00:42:48.440
challenging feature.

00:42:48.440 --> 00:42:52.160
One interpretation,
one is of a school

00:42:52.160 --> 00:42:54.120
pushed by people
like Phil Zimbardo

00:42:54.120 --> 00:42:57.330
here in the psychology
department, incredibly

00:42:57.330 --> 00:43:01.130
influential psychologist, who as
a general theme over the years

00:43:01.130 --> 00:43:04.600
has argued for the stance that
under the right circumstances,

00:43:04.600 --> 00:43:07.000
under the right
coercive circumstances,

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:10.940
virtually anybody could do
anything that is appalling.

00:43:10.940 --> 00:43:15.180
Zimbardo, who did the famed
Stanford prison study.

00:43:15.180 --> 00:43:18.420
The other view is, OK,
this isn't a lesson

00:43:18.420 --> 00:43:22.927
that anybody could wind up being
this violent if, look at them.

00:43:22.927 --> 00:43:23.760
They're an engineer.

00:43:23.760 --> 00:43:26.260
And they've got a master's
degree, and all of that.

00:43:26.260 --> 00:43:30.270
Instead, it is simply an outcome
of a lot of what terrorism

00:43:30.270 --> 00:43:33.320
is about these days,
a very novel world

00:43:33.320 --> 00:43:36.000
of international terrorism.

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:38.560
Rather than within
country, suddenly you

00:43:38.560 --> 00:43:41.460
have a world of people who
need to be able to do things

00:43:41.460 --> 00:43:45.410
like get passports, and
fly elsewhere, and be

00:43:45.410 --> 00:43:48.760
able to navigate customs,
and things of that sort.

00:43:48.760 --> 00:43:52.150
It is suddenly selecting for a
more sophisticated population

00:43:52.150 --> 00:43:53.540
of individuals.

00:43:53.540 --> 00:43:55.450
You know, the jury's
out on all of this.

00:43:55.450 --> 00:43:58.280
But this seems to be a
very challenging thing

00:43:58.280 --> 00:44:00.310
for that field.

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:04.340
OK, so now this allows us to
push one step further back.

00:44:04.340 --> 00:44:06.480
I'm going to skip over
a few things there.

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:09.870
Now, insofar as we are
looking at culture,

00:44:09.870 --> 00:44:13.080
and insofar as we have looked
at anthropological differences,

00:44:13.080 --> 00:44:15.730
and insofar as we have
looked at anything having

00:44:15.730 --> 00:44:19.350
to do with genes, we now
have to talk about evolution,

00:44:19.350 --> 00:44:22.330
because that's where the
genes came from, of course.

00:44:22.330 --> 00:44:24.860
So in first pass,
it's absolutely simple

00:44:24.860 --> 00:44:27.600
to understand what evolution
has to do with aggression, which

00:44:27.600 --> 00:44:31.080
is evolution selects for higher
and higher levels of aggression

00:44:31.080 --> 00:44:33.420
because that's what
you need to succeed.

00:44:33.420 --> 00:44:35.860
Unless you grew up watching
certain types of television

00:44:35.860 --> 00:44:38.150
programs, in which
case evolution selects

00:44:38.150 --> 00:44:40.460
for no aggression
occurring because animals

00:44:40.460 --> 00:44:42.960
behave for the good
of the species.

00:44:42.960 --> 00:44:45.130
So sorting through
that, beginning now

00:44:45.130 --> 00:44:48.230
to apply some of our
foundations from that world,

00:44:48.230 --> 00:44:53.480
individual selection, kin
selection, reciprocal altruism,

00:44:53.480 --> 00:44:56.910
and the modern version
of group selection.

00:44:56.910 --> 00:44:58.610
So where do these play out?

00:44:58.610 --> 00:45:01.030
First, how do these
play out in terms

00:45:01.030 --> 00:45:05.020
of increasing the likelihood
of aggression and antisocial

00:45:05.020 --> 00:45:06.430
behavior?

00:45:06.430 --> 00:45:10.810
Individual selection, males,
that is absolutely simple.

00:45:10.810 --> 00:45:16.270
In every culture on this
planet, and in the vast majority

00:45:16.270 --> 00:45:18.710
of social species that
have been looked at,

00:45:18.710 --> 00:45:21.560
the majority, the major
cause of aggression

00:45:21.560 --> 00:45:25.030
in that society or species
is male male violence

00:45:25.030 --> 00:45:27.820
over reproductive
access to females.

00:45:27.820 --> 00:45:30.340
That is close to a universal.

00:45:30.340 --> 00:45:33.060
That is the most
common form motivator

00:45:33.060 --> 00:45:36.370
of violence on this planet,
humans and otherwise.

00:45:36.370 --> 00:45:38.630
So that one's easy
to come up with,

00:45:38.630 --> 00:45:40.850
in terms of obvious stuff.

00:45:40.850 --> 00:45:44.920
One classic study,
insanely controversial one,

00:45:44.920 --> 00:45:48.680
that appeared to be the
landmark demonstration of some

00:45:48.680 --> 00:45:52.090
of the same in humans--
traditional tribe,

00:45:52.090 --> 00:45:55.480
hunter-gatherer down in
Venezuela in the Amazon

00:45:55.480 --> 00:45:58.080
called the Yanomamo
who have been

00:45:58.080 --> 00:46:01.130
the darlings of high
testosterone male

00:46:01.130 --> 00:46:03.290
anthropologists for decades.

00:46:03.290 --> 00:46:07.430
These have been intensely
studied people, many decades

00:46:07.430 --> 00:46:09.690
now, predominantly by
an anthropologist named

00:46:09.690 --> 00:46:13.060
Napoleon Chagnon, who is now
emeritus at Santa Barbara.

00:46:13.060 --> 00:46:15.550
But he has been a major
figure in anthropology

00:46:15.550 --> 00:46:16.760
for a long time.

00:46:16.760 --> 00:46:21.380
And these people are insanely
aggressive, incredibly high

00:46:21.380 --> 00:46:25.090
rates of violence between
groups, within groups.

00:46:25.090 --> 00:46:28.630
Sufficiently so that
the written monographs

00:46:28.630 --> 00:46:30.663
of the Yanamamo, with
titles like Yanamamo,

00:46:30.663 --> 00:46:33.420
the fierce people,
things of that sort.

00:46:33.420 --> 00:46:36.360
And about 15 years ago,
Chagnon published a paper

00:46:36.360 --> 00:46:39.630
in Science using
decade's worth of data

00:46:39.630 --> 00:46:44.700
showing that the more people,
particular men in this society,

00:46:44.700 --> 00:46:48.760
in this tribe, the more people
you have killed on the average,

00:46:48.760 --> 00:46:51.700
the higher your
reproductive success

00:46:51.700 --> 00:46:52.532
That's it.

00:46:52.532 --> 00:46:53.364
That's it.

00:46:53.364 --> 00:46:54.900
That's everything right there.

00:46:54.900 --> 00:46:56.680
That's Darwin all
over the place.

00:46:56.680 --> 00:46:58.380
Just play it out over time.

00:46:58.380 --> 00:47:02.760
And this is dramatic selection
in a traditional human society,

00:47:02.760 --> 00:47:07.390
the reproductive rewards
of violence and murder.

00:47:07.390 --> 00:47:10.290
Very major, influential
study, picked up

00:47:10.290 --> 00:47:11.520
by all the newspapers.

00:47:11.520 --> 00:47:14.330
And it has been completely
mired in controversy

00:47:14.330 --> 00:47:18.730
ever since, all sorts of
ethical attacks on Chagnon,

00:47:18.730 --> 00:47:20.240
most of which that
have not stuck,

00:47:20.240 --> 00:47:23.910
but some really, really telling
dissections of the work,

00:47:23.910 --> 00:47:26.140
ripping it apart on
statistical grounds.

00:47:26.140 --> 00:47:28.790
I don't think it's
actually for real.

00:47:28.790 --> 00:47:32.740
But that as easily interpreted
within that framework.

00:47:32.740 --> 00:47:35.830
Then more realms of violence,
individual selection,

00:47:35.830 --> 00:47:39.570
orangutans raping each,
rape in other species,

00:47:39.570 --> 00:47:42.180
rape among humans, which
of course brings up

00:47:42.180 --> 00:47:45.650
the question of whether
rape is more about passing

00:47:45.650 --> 00:47:49.850
on copies of your genes, or more
about power and subjugation.

00:47:49.850 --> 00:47:51.800
And the overwhelming
sense in the field

00:47:51.800 --> 00:47:53.760
is it's about the latter.

00:47:53.760 --> 00:47:57.460
It does not have a whole
lot to do with a world

00:47:57.460 --> 00:48:00.330
where you have to start counting
numbers of copies of genes,

00:48:00.330 --> 00:48:04.260
and thinking about
adaptiveness of strategies.

00:48:04.260 --> 00:48:08.280
Next, individual selection,
explaining another realm

00:48:08.280 --> 00:48:11.560
of violence-- in most
cultures, and in an awful lot

00:48:11.560 --> 00:48:15.460
of species looked at, the
second leading cause of violence

00:48:15.460 --> 00:48:22.360
is males attacking females
over denial of sexual access.

00:48:22.360 --> 00:48:27.280
And this is amazingly
common all over the place,

00:48:27.280 --> 00:48:29.490
the second leading
cause of violence

00:48:29.490 --> 00:48:32.620
on this planet across humans
and different cultures,

00:48:32.620 --> 00:48:37.630
and obvious easy individual
selection explanation there.

00:48:37.630 --> 00:48:40.550
Finally, another realm
individual selection,

00:48:40.550 --> 00:48:43.490
the world of female
female competition,

00:48:43.490 --> 00:48:46.360
and infanticide,
competitive infanticide.

00:48:46.360 --> 00:48:47.980
We know how to run all of those.

00:48:47.980 --> 00:48:50.240
So lots of reasons
within the framework

00:48:50.240 --> 00:48:53.230
of individual selection
to see where you are

00:48:53.230 --> 00:48:55.420
increasing rates of aggression.

00:48:55.420 --> 00:48:59.270
Next, kin selection-- you're
going to know that one as well.

00:48:59.270 --> 00:49:02.780
Two brothers or eight cousins,
and that whole strategy,

00:49:02.780 --> 00:49:05.370
and that's why
related individuals

00:49:05.370 --> 00:49:09.280
cooperate with each other in
circumstances of aggression.

00:49:09.280 --> 00:49:13.970
Chimpanzees--
chimps are function

00:49:13.970 --> 00:49:16.430
where females are the ones
who pick up at puberty

00:49:16.430 --> 00:49:17.490
and go elsewhere.

00:49:17.490 --> 00:49:20.070
So all of the adult
males in a chimp group

00:49:20.070 --> 00:49:23.730
are brothers, first cousins,
things of that sort.

00:49:23.730 --> 00:49:26.620
And, thus, you get
one of the outcomes

00:49:26.620 --> 00:49:29.850
of that, high levels of
male male cooperation.

00:49:29.850 --> 00:49:33.630
And as we heard, that has been
reported by Goodall and others

00:49:33.630 --> 00:49:36.250
to result in things
that look absolutely

00:49:36.250 --> 00:49:39.140
like organized
warfare and genocide,

00:49:39.140 --> 00:49:42.460
eradicating all the males in
a group in the next valley

00:49:42.460 --> 00:49:46.190
over, purely along
kinship lines.

00:49:46.190 --> 00:49:47.640
What else?

00:49:47.640 --> 00:49:51.440
Other primates, old world
primates, monkeys like baboons,

00:49:51.440 --> 00:49:55.530
aggression is very much
between lineages than within,

00:49:55.530 --> 00:49:58.600
same exact kin selection
sort of arguments.

00:49:58.600 --> 00:50:00.620
So what happens when
you get to humans?

00:50:00.620 --> 00:50:03.960
Things get more
complicated, of course.

00:50:03.960 --> 00:50:07.675
The first one being that
a relative, relatives,

00:50:07.675 --> 00:50:12.510
is a relative term, in
that it is a sliding scale.

00:50:12.510 --> 00:50:15.440
Wonderful quote to that
effect, a Bedouin quote,

00:50:15.440 --> 00:50:19.700
which is, it's my
brothers, my cousins, and I

00:50:19.700 --> 00:50:21.820
against the world.

00:50:21.820 --> 00:50:26.140
And it's my brothers and
I against my cousins.

00:50:26.140 --> 00:50:29.160
As in, who counts as an
us, and who counts as a

00:50:29.160 --> 00:50:31.280
them is a sliding measure.

00:50:31.280 --> 00:50:33.620
It is a relative measure.

00:50:33.620 --> 00:50:35.540
What you see is by
the time you get

00:50:35.540 --> 00:50:40.210
to humans capacity for very
rapid shifts of us/them

00:50:40.210 --> 00:50:43.040
along the lines of relatedness.

00:50:43.040 --> 00:50:45.680
Now, one of the readings,
which I can't remember now

00:50:45.680 --> 00:50:48.190
if I actually did stick
into an assignment,

00:50:48.190 --> 00:50:52.270
but one of the readings looks
at the classic social biological

00:50:52.270 --> 00:50:55.370
interpretation of making
sense of aggression

00:50:55.370 --> 00:50:57.070
along the lines
of kin selection.

00:50:57.070 --> 00:51:00.360
What do you make of child abuse?

00:51:00.360 --> 00:51:04.020
What do you make of homicidal
parents, damaging parents?

00:51:04.020 --> 00:51:07.620
How do you make sense of that
in a, are you out of your mind?

00:51:07.620 --> 00:51:11.510
This is copies of your genes
there, the challenges to that.

00:51:11.510 --> 00:51:15.280
And this is a couple, Daley and
Wilson, University of Toronto,

00:51:15.280 --> 00:51:17.690
I think, who have for
decades been working

00:51:17.690 --> 00:51:22.440
in this area showing
things like a child is

00:51:22.440 --> 00:51:26.470
more likely to be
abused by a stepfather

00:51:26.470 --> 00:51:28.500
than a biological father.

00:51:28.500 --> 00:51:30.120
Wonder what that's about?

00:51:30.120 --> 00:51:32.380
Kin selection, that's easy.

00:51:32.380 --> 00:51:34.410
A child is more
likely to be abused

00:51:34.410 --> 00:51:38.760
by a paternal grandparent
than a maternal one.

00:51:38.760 --> 00:51:42.500
Kin selection explanation--
more certainty of paternity

00:51:42.500 --> 00:51:45.130
when something is going
through a female line.

00:51:45.130 --> 00:51:46.840
So they've been
all these studies

00:51:46.840 --> 00:51:50.040
showing that degree
of relatedness

00:51:50.040 --> 00:51:52.830
explains a fair amount of
the variability in patterns

00:51:52.830 --> 00:51:56.280
of violence within families.

00:51:56.280 --> 00:51:58.790
Problems with it--
two problems, one

00:51:58.790 --> 00:52:01.710
is there's been a lot of
failure of replications

00:52:01.710 --> 00:52:03.120
in other societies.

00:52:03.120 --> 00:52:06.400
The Scandinavians, for
example, don't see that pattern

00:52:06.400 --> 00:52:07.420
when they study it.

00:52:07.420 --> 00:52:09.850
The other is there's
alternative models.

00:52:09.850 --> 00:52:12.330
There's economic
models, for example.

00:52:12.330 --> 00:52:17.050
When times get tough in
terms of displacement,

00:52:17.050 --> 00:52:18.940
family violence increases.

00:52:18.940 --> 00:52:21.630
Families with stepfathers,
on the average,

00:52:21.630 --> 00:52:23.970
are under more economic
duress than families

00:52:23.970 --> 00:52:27.820
with biological fathers, greater
likelihood of violence there.

00:52:27.820 --> 00:52:30.440
It is a very
uncontrolled literature.

00:52:30.440 --> 00:52:33.022
That is sort of viewed
as in the classic,

00:52:33.022 --> 00:52:36.620
and in other people's view, the
most ideologically most extreme

00:52:36.620 --> 00:52:39.760
way in which social biologists
think about something as

00:52:39.760 --> 00:52:44.560
bizarre and challenging as close
relatives killing each other.

00:52:44.560 --> 00:52:48.760
One final realm, which is in
terms of this us/them stuff,

00:52:48.760 --> 00:52:52.630
the point here being, how do you
decide who is an us and them?

00:52:52.630 --> 00:52:55.860
And suddenly, we're in
our world of ethology.

00:52:55.860 --> 00:53:00.390
Do we make some us/them
dichotomies more easily

00:53:00.390 --> 00:53:01.520
than others?

00:53:01.520 --> 00:53:04.580
Do we have prepared
learning to see

00:53:04.580 --> 00:53:09.460
some differences as more
salient than others in us/thems?

00:53:09.460 --> 00:53:12.740
That remains an immensely
controversial subject

00:53:12.740 --> 00:53:16.530
in terms of what are the natural
categories that young kids

00:53:16.530 --> 00:53:18.320
divide people up by?

00:53:18.320 --> 00:53:21.950
Are kids colorblind in
terms of skin color?

00:53:21.950 --> 00:53:25.020
Are kids blind in
terms of body types,

00:53:25.020 --> 00:53:26.340
in terms of some such things?

00:53:26.340 --> 00:53:29.680
Lots of work in this
area, how unnatural

00:53:29.680 --> 00:53:31.740
are some of the
us/them dichotomies

00:53:31.740 --> 00:53:33.190
that we tend to come up with?

