Revolutions generating
pseudo kinship,

01:06:36.310 --> 01:06:39.280
what is often the term
people use for each other

01:06:39.280 --> 01:06:40.920
after the revolution?

01:06:40.920 --> 01:06:45.190
Sisters, brothers unite,
pseudo kinship terms.

01:06:45.190 --> 01:06:50.300
In French, for example, there
is in the informal to tense.

01:06:50.300 --> 01:06:51.695
And there's the more formal one.

01:06:51.695 --> 01:06:54.540
And you're supposed to
use the more formal run

01:06:54.540 --> 01:06:55.810
sort of in the outside world.

01:06:55.810 --> 01:06:58.380
And in the aftermath of
the French Revolution,

01:06:58.380 --> 01:07:02.130
it became illegal to address
somebody, a stranger,

01:07:02.130 --> 01:07:03.630
in the formal tense.

01:07:03.630 --> 01:07:06.070
It always had to be
with the familial

01:07:06.070 --> 01:07:11.010
to tense there, pseudo
kinship, more and more of it.

01:07:11.010 --> 01:07:13.690
So this brings up
what is initially

01:07:13.690 --> 01:07:18.250
a really, really depressing
set of studies, which turn out

01:07:18.250 --> 01:07:22.010
to have a very nice optimistic
resolution to them--

01:07:22.010 --> 01:07:24.230
very disturbing work.

01:07:24.230 --> 01:07:26.850
Work done by a number
of labs over the years

01:07:26.850 --> 01:07:32.340
most notably, Elizabeth
Phelps, who is at NYU.

01:07:32.340 --> 01:07:35.300
And this is work using
functional brain imaging,

01:07:35.300 --> 01:07:36.600
amygdala, all of that.

01:07:36.600 --> 01:07:39.300
You put people in
a brain scanner.

01:07:39.300 --> 01:07:40.690
Actually you put one in.

01:07:40.690 --> 01:07:42.420
And you put them
in one at a time.

01:07:42.420 --> 01:07:46.570
And what you do is you're
flashing up pictures to them,

01:07:46.570 --> 01:07:49.980
flashing up pictures
of people, of faces,

01:07:49.980 --> 01:07:52.200
of faces at a rapid speed.

01:07:52.200 --> 01:07:54.860
So there's virtually no
conscious processing.

01:07:54.860 --> 01:07:57.620
This is all tapping
into subliminal stuff.

01:07:57.620 --> 01:08:00.870
And what she reported, and
what has been replicated

01:08:00.870 --> 01:08:03.780
by a number of other
groups since then,

01:08:03.780 --> 01:08:08.010
is that you get
activation of the amygdala

01:08:08.010 --> 01:08:10.470
on the average in people
when you subliminally

01:08:10.470 --> 01:08:15.720
flash up pictures of
somebody of another race.

01:08:15.720 --> 01:08:20.149
Whoa, shit, that is
distressing to have been found.

01:08:20.149 --> 01:08:22.920
That is not a good
thing, because this

01:08:22.920 --> 01:08:27.290
is totally rapid subliminal
stuff, and replicated,

01:08:27.290 --> 01:08:29.830
some of the best people
in the field showing this.

01:08:29.830 --> 01:08:33.290
My God, the amygdala
has an us/them

01:08:33.290 --> 01:08:35.229
that's, in effect,
there in a quarter

01:08:35.229 --> 01:08:37.060
second after seeing something.

01:08:37.060 --> 01:08:38.510
This is hopeless.

01:08:38.510 --> 01:08:40.660
We are so dichotomized.

01:08:40.660 --> 01:08:43.060
This is a disaster.

01:08:43.060 --> 01:08:46.270
In the years since then,
much more interesting stuff

01:08:46.270 --> 01:08:47.010
has emerged.

01:08:47.010 --> 01:08:48.930
And this has predominately
been research

01:08:48.930 --> 01:08:53.160
by Susan Fiske at Princeton
showing that it doesn't

01:08:53.160 --> 01:08:55.420
necessarily work this way.

01:08:55.420 --> 01:08:58.090
OK, here's what you do.

01:08:58.090 --> 01:09:00.520
First version,
you tell somebody,

01:09:00.520 --> 01:09:02.100
I'm going to be
flashing up pictures

01:09:02.100 --> 01:09:05.319
of faces while you're lying
there in the brain scanner.

01:09:05.319 --> 01:09:07.790
And what you do
is you force them

01:09:07.790 --> 01:09:10.859
to look at the picture in
a way where in a purely

01:09:10.859 --> 01:09:14.020
mechanical visual viewing,
you're going to say,

01:09:14.020 --> 01:09:17.177
some of the pictures
have a big red dot

01:09:17.177 --> 01:09:18.260
right in the middle of it.

01:09:18.260 --> 01:09:19.718
And any time one
of those comes up,

01:09:19.718 --> 01:09:21.490
I want you to press this button.

01:09:21.490 --> 01:09:24.580
In other words, just
process the picture

01:09:24.580 --> 01:09:27.060
for just a visual pattern.

01:09:27.060 --> 01:09:27.990
You do that.

01:09:27.990 --> 01:09:29.750
And the amygdala
doesn't activate

01:09:29.750 --> 01:09:32.160
when you see a picture of
somebody of another race.

01:09:32.160 --> 01:09:34.620
OK, this is not very exciting.

01:09:34.620 --> 01:09:37.390
Now, the next thing
she would do--

01:09:37.390 --> 01:09:41.090
get people to start
thinking categorically.

01:09:41.090 --> 01:09:41.939
Here's what you do.

01:09:41.939 --> 01:09:43.939
She would now have people
going in there saying,

01:09:43.939 --> 01:09:46.605
I'm going to give you a bunch of
pictures, flashing up pictures.

01:09:46.605 --> 01:09:49.653
And what I want you
to do is to stop.

01:09:49.653 --> 01:09:51.069
I'm going to stop
at some of them.

01:09:51.069 --> 01:09:52.520
And I want you to look closely.

01:09:52.520 --> 01:09:56.020
And tell me, do you think
this person is older than age

01:09:56.020 --> 01:09:59.030
30 or younger than age 30?

01:09:59.030 --> 01:10:02.710
In other words, what you have
just requested the person to do

01:10:02.710 --> 01:10:04.570
is think of the
face in the picture

01:10:04.570 --> 01:10:09.542
as belonging to a category,
rather than as an individual.

01:10:09.542 --> 01:10:11.250
You're going to look
at this picture now.

01:10:11.250 --> 01:10:13.450
And you don't really need
to care who the person is,

01:10:13.450 --> 01:10:15.090
or what they look
like, or anything.

01:10:15.090 --> 01:10:18.900
All you need to do is think
of them as part of a category.

01:10:18.900 --> 01:10:20.740
And when you bias
people like that,

01:10:20.740 --> 01:10:23.810
and you flash up the picture
of somebody from another race,

01:10:23.810 --> 01:10:26.330
the amygdala gets
even more activated.

01:10:26.330 --> 01:10:30.450
You have primed somebody to
think not about individuals,

01:10:30.450 --> 01:10:33.930
but to make them think
of people in categories.

01:10:33.930 --> 01:10:37.790
Finally, what she shows
is exactly the opposite.

01:10:37.790 --> 01:10:40.160
Now what she does
is prime something,

01:10:40.160 --> 01:10:42.640
a totally neutral
sort of priming,

01:10:42.640 --> 01:10:46.010
to try to get people to think
of the person in the picture

01:10:46.010 --> 01:10:47.660
as an individual.

01:10:47.660 --> 01:10:51.550
And she asks totally
innocuous, neutral things

01:10:51.550 --> 01:10:53.910
along the lines of, I want
you to look at the picture.

01:10:53.910 --> 01:10:54.952
I know this sounds silly.

01:10:54.952 --> 01:10:56.534
But I want you to
look at the picture.

01:10:56.534 --> 01:10:58.930
And tell me, do you think is
this the kind of person who

01:10:58.930 --> 01:11:02.300
likes Coke or Pepsi?

01:11:02.300 --> 01:11:04.490
Totally sort of
diagonal orthogonal

01:11:04.490 --> 01:11:07.320
to all of this stuff,
get someone doing that.

01:11:07.320 --> 01:11:11.770
And now the amygdala
doesn't activate.

01:11:11.770 --> 01:11:17.110
All you need to do in that study
is subliminally prime someone

01:11:17.110 --> 01:11:19.450
to think of someone who
they're about to look

01:11:19.450 --> 01:11:23.630
at as an individual, rather
than as part of a category,

01:11:23.630 --> 01:11:25.280
than as part of a group.

01:11:25.280 --> 01:11:29.860
This is not rebuilding society
so that we change our us/thems.

01:11:29.860 --> 01:11:33.580
This is a minor prompt 30
seconds before somebody has

01:11:33.580 --> 01:11:35.130
the pictures flashed at them.

01:11:35.130 --> 01:11:38.270
That's all it took
in these studies.

01:11:38.270 --> 01:11:41.780
More good news emerged,
which was that you would also

01:11:41.780 --> 01:11:44.440
see separate of these
sorts of manipulations,

01:11:44.440 --> 01:11:47.970
long-term developmental
aspects that were predictors

01:11:47.970 --> 01:11:49.130
of this phenomenon.

01:11:49.130 --> 01:11:53.060
People who grew up in racially
and ethnically diverse

01:11:53.060 --> 01:11:56.640
neighborhoods didn't have
this amygdala effect.

01:11:56.640 --> 01:11:59.360
People who had had a
significant relationship

01:11:59.360 --> 01:12:02.500
with a significant
other of another race

01:12:02.500 --> 01:12:05.450
did not have this
amygdala reaction there.

01:12:05.450 --> 01:12:09.200
So the easy solution to
this being depressing--

01:12:09.200 --> 01:12:14.200
OK, early childhood, exposure
throughout life, that's great.

01:12:14.200 --> 01:12:15.520
That's very good news.

01:12:15.520 --> 01:12:19.470
But even more remarkable in
her studies is just a prompt.

01:12:19.470 --> 01:12:23.290
Prompt somebody to think of
that person as an individual.

01:12:23.290 --> 01:12:28.300
And your amygdala is not doing
an us/them with them anymore.

01:12:28.300 --> 01:12:31.160
Now, this whole business
about if you grew up

01:12:31.160 --> 01:12:35.070
in a diverse neighborhood,
that taps into a whole field

01:12:35.070 --> 01:12:37.100
called contact theory.

01:12:37.100 --> 01:12:39.460
The notion that
aggression is decreased,

01:12:39.460 --> 01:12:43.090
affiliation is increased,
if people have grown up

01:12:43.090 --> 01:12:46.850
with lots of contact with
people from other cultures,

01:12:46.850 --> 01:12:50.010
other societies other
religions, all of that,

01:12:50.010 --> 01:12:53.430
or if people live
in contact with it.

01:12:53.430 --> 01:12:56.780
And, in general, what this
large literature shows is

01:12:56.780 --> 01:12:58.280
it does work that way.

01:12:58.280 --> 01:13:01.950
Contact theory, growing up
in diverse neighborhoods,

01:13:01.950 --> 01:13:03.940
growing up in
diverse communities,

01:13:03.940 --> 01:13:07.310
increases the likelihood
of a broader umbrella

01:13:07.310 --> 01:13:10.490
of what counts as an us.

01:13:10.490 --> 01:13:11.440
That's good.

01:13:11.440 --> 01:13:13.160
Where does it not work?

01:13:13.160 --> 01:13:16.060
One realm where most of
the studies have shown this

01:13:16.060 --> 01:13:18.710
is a realm that's
totally heartwarming.

01:13:18.710 --> 01:13:20.560
And it would be
great if it did work.

01:13:20.560 --> 01:13:23.010
But most of the studies
show that it doesn't.

01:13:23.010 --> 01:13:25.660
These are the circumstances
where somebody puts up

01:13:25.660 --> 01:13:29.650
the money to take some really
poor Irish Catholic kids

01:13:29.650 --> 01:13:34.210
in Belfast, and some really poor
Irish Protestant kids in there

01:13:34.210 --> 01:13:36.570
during the worst of
the civil unrest there.

01:13:36.570 --> 01:13:39.820
And they get to go to someplace
wonderful and far away.

01:13:39.820 --> 01:13:42.730
And they all go to
summer camp together.

01:13:42.730 --> 01:13:45.220
And they have teams that
are mixtures of the kids

01:13:45.220 --> 01:13:46.340
by different religions.

01:13:46.340 --> 01:13:47.480
And they're growing.

01:13:47.480 --> 01:13:50.390
They're growing to recognize
each other as individuals.

01:13:50.390 --> 01:13:53.010
Or the versions, lots of
which have been tried,

01:13:53.010 --> 01:13:58.030
of sort of retreats or even
camps of Palestinian teenagers,

01:13:58.030 --> 01:13:59.560
Israeli teenagers.

01:13:59.560 --> 01:14:01.210
These are the leaders
in the future.

01:14:01.210 --> 01:14:03.860
They will go back and
have learned they're not

01:14:03.860 --> 01:14:05.340
so different after all.

01:14:05.340 --> 01:14:07.220
They're kind of just like us.

01:14:07.220 --> 01:14:09.030
What those studies
have generally shown

01:14:09.030 --> 01:14:10.720
is that doesn't work.

01:14:10.720 --> 01:14:12.650
It works for only
a little while.

01:14:12.650 --> 01:14:16.130
You can't just pull it off
on a two-week camping trip.

01:14:16.130 --> 01:14:18.420
It takes more
sustained exposure.

01:14:18.420 --> 01:14:23.620
It basically requires growing
up in, or living sustainedly in.

01:14:23.620 --> 01:14:25.630
So that's been a disappointment.

01:14:25.630 --> 01:14:28.280
One additional disappointment
with the contact theory

01:14:28.280 --> 01:14:38.510
literature, which is one of the
papers, which again I think I

01:14:38.510 --> 01:14:39.770
put in the suggested reading.

01:14:39.770 --> 01:14:41.830
OK, so you've got
two different groups,

01:14:41.830 --> 01:14:44.240
two different populations,
two different ethnicities,

01:14:44.240 --> 01:14:45.160
whatever.

01:14:45.160 --> 01:14:48.440
And they are living in
generally the same area,

01:14:48.440 --> 01:14:52.650
but nonetheless segregated
within group in smaller areas.

01:14:52.650 --> 01:14:57.270
One scenario-- here's the region
where these two groups live.

01:14:57.270 --> 01:15:00.650
And there's an absolute
boundary between them.

01:15:00.650 --> 01:15:04.450
Here, instead, there's sort
of an undulating boundary.

01:15:04.450 --> 01:15:05.630
It's less clear.

01:15:05.630 --> 01:15:09.240
And, critically, there
is more surface area.

01:15:09.240 --> 01:15:12.860
There is more interfaces
between the two groups.

01:15:12.860 --> 01:15:16.320
There's more domains
of experiencing people

01:15:16.320 --> 01:15:17.840
from the other group.

01:15:17.840 --> 01:15:20.810
Finally, versions
where instead you

01:15:20.810 --> 01:15:24.350
have pockets of different
groups embedded in other ones.

01:15:24.350 --> 01:15:27.120
And that being a completely
different scenario

01:15:27.120 --> 01:15:31.770
where, in fact, you maximize the
perimeter that you get there.

01:15:31.770 --> 01:15:33.450
And what's been shown
in this one study

01:15:33.450 --> 01:15:37.320
that I recommended that you
guys look at is the more

01:15:37.320 --> 01:15:40.450
contact, the more
interfaces, between the two

01:15:40.450 --> 01:15:44.380
groups and living situations
doesn't guarantee that people

01:15:44.380 --> 01:15:45.830
will get along better.

01:15:45.830 --> 01:15:48.790
What you will find is there's
intermediate points where

01:15:48.790 --> 01:15:52.390
the contact profile
increases aggression,

01:15:52.390 --> 01:15:55.100
because what it does
is you just barely

01:15:55.100 --> 01:15:59.100
have a critical mass
of people on your side

01:15:59.100 --> 01:16:02.510
to be an effective group
to fight with them.

01:16:02.510 --> 01:16:04.390
You see totally
different outcomes,

01:16:04.390 --> 01:16:06.980
depending on the
spatial characteristics

01:16:06.980 --> 01:16:07.930
of the subgrouping.

01:16:07.930 --> 01:16:09.890
And what the people
showed in this paper was

01:16:09.890 --> 01:16:13.120
they then analyzed the
different ethnic distributions

01:16:13.120 --> 01:16:17.190
in the Balkans, the Bosnian
War, the Croatians, all of that,

01:16:17.190 --> 01:16:20.740
and seeing that this was
extremely predictive of where

01:16:20.740 --> 01:16:24.500
the violence took place in
terms of where you had what they

01:16:24.500 --> 01:16:29.000
viewed as the least optimal
set of interfaces of contact

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:30.010
between groups.

01:16:30.010 --> 01:16:33.120
More contact is not
necessarily always equal,

01:16:33.120 --> 01:16:35.750
more understanding and
we're all just the same.

01:16:35.750 --> 01:16:39.790
More contact can equal, in
some cases, more irritation,

01:16:39.790 --> 01:16:44.710
and more resources, and more
unity to do something about it.

01:16:44.710 --> 01:16:49.650
OK, more of pseudo kinship--
so this whole notion, again,

01:16:49.650 --> 01:16:52.190
of pseudo kinship,
we are species

01:16:52.190 --> 01:16:53.900
where we're not
recognizing individuals

01:16:53.900 --> 01:16:55.260
by smell, all of that.

01:16:55.260 --> 01:16:57.252
We're doing that
cognition stuff.

01:16:57.252 --> 01:16:58.960
But don't forget the
[? kibbutz ?] study.

01:16:58.960 --> 01:17:00.800
But we're doing that
cognition stuff.

01:17:00.800 --> 01:17:03.080
And, thus, we can
do pseudo kinship.

01:17:03.080 --> 01:17:05.550
And, thus, we could
be manipulated

01:17:05.550 --> 01:17:09.390
by powers that be, by
governments, by religions,

01:17:09.390 --> 01:17:12.700
and to viewing non-relatives
as more related to us,

01:17:12.700 --> 01:17:13.500
and all of that.

01:17:13.500 --> 01:17:16.680
These are very
abstract processes.

01:17:16.680 --> 01:17:20.470
And it brings up another realm,
an extremely abstract realm,

01:17:20.470 --> 01:17:24.614
that pushes for more
cooperation and less violence.

01:17:24.614 --> 01:17:26.280
And this goes back
to what I was talking

01:17:26.280 --> 01:17:29.630
about the other day, the
neurobiology of symbols,

01:17:29.630 --> 01:17:32.180
how we code for certain
types of symbols,

01:17:32.180 --> 01:17:33.870
certain metaphors in our brain.

01:17:33.870 --> 01:17:35.550
And that's back to
that whole world

01:17:35.550 --> 01:17:37.940
of, you're using the
same part of the brain

01:17:37.940 --> 01:17:41.650
for disgusting food and
moral disgust, warm drink,

01:17:41.650 --> 01:17:45.282
warm personality, that
weird concrete literalness.

01:17:45.282 --> 01:17:47.240
Because you've got a
pretty metaphors somewhere

01:17:47.240 --> 01:17:49.310
when humans started
developing them,

01:17:49.310 --> 01:17:51.520
the outcome of that
being that metaphors

01:17:51.520 --> 01:17:54.750
can be extraordinarily powerful.

01:17:54.750 --> 01:17:56.500
And a number of
researchers-- probably

01:17:56.500 --> 01:17:59.320
the person most visible in
this realm, an economist

01:17:59.320 --> 01:18:01.780
University of Michigan
named Robert Axelrod

01:18:01.780 --> 01:18:04.770
as doing a whole lot of
work showing, in a sense,

01:18:04.770 --> 01:18:08.040
the importance of
symbols in peacemaking.

01:18:08.040 --> 01:18:10.020
And it makes perfect sense.

01:18:10.020 --> 01:18:13.060
You take the extreme
rationalist view

01:18:13.060 --> 01:18:15.490
of humans as economic machines.

01:18:15.490 --> 01:18:18.250
And what peacemaking is
going to be purely about

01:18:18.250 --> 01:18:21.300
is figuring out
contested resources

01:18:21.300 --> 01:18:23.780
and how they are going
to be divided up.

01:18:23.780 --> 01:18:25.620
And what Axelrod
and others show,

01:18:25.620 --> 01:18:29.700
instead, is this whole
irrational realm of,

01:18:29.700 --> 01:18:33.520
be respectful of
somebody else's symbols.

01:18:33.520 --> 01:18:36.700
And figuring out how you're
going to divide up the land

01:18:36.700 --> 01:18:39.070
suddenly becomes a
lot less important--

01:18:39.070 --> 01:18:43.590
the power of symbols over
rational contested resources.

01:18:43.590 --> 01:18:47.040
And he studied things like
how a critical thing that

01:18:47.040 --> 01:18:50.280
happened in peace coming
to Northern Ireland

01:18:50.280 --> 01:18:54.580
was at one juncture a bunch
of the Sinn Fein, however

01:18:54.580 --> 01:18:58.510
that's pronounced, the
ex-military wing of the IRA

01:18:58.510 --> 01:19:01.500
that were just beginning
to have extremely

01:19:01.500 --> 01:19:06.180
mistrustful negotiations with
some of the Protestant unions

01:19:06.180 --> 01:19:06.900
and all of that.

01:19:06.900 --> 01:19:09.210
They did something outrageous.

01:19:09.210 --> 01:19:12.100
They sent a 50th
wedding anniversary gift

01:19:12.100 --> 01:19:16.180
to this guy Ian Paisley,
who was the murderous head

01:19:16.180 --> 01:19:18.950
of the Protestant
death squads there.

01:19:18.950 --> 01:19:21.400
Somebody just
decided to try this.

01:19:21.400 --> 01:19:24.590
And this was a
massive breakthrough.

01:19:24.590 --> 01:19:27.830
Anyone who saw that movie
Invictus or have read about,

01:19:27.830 --> 01:19:30.140
the utter brilliance
of Nelson Mandela,

01:19:30.140 --> 01:19:32.920
of having spent his
time in prison learning

01:19:32.920 --> 01:19:35.650
to be completely
fluent in Afrikaans

01:19:35.650 --> 01:19:39.180
so that when he was sitting
down and starting to negotiate

01:19:39.180 --> 01:19:42.690
with these people, the fact that
he could sit there and speak

01:19:42.690 --> 01:19:44.480
in their language,
a language that

01:19:44.480 --> 01:19:47.390
is so laden with
symbolic importance

01:19:47.390 --> 01:19:51.710
to Afrikaners, that that
was a gigantic symbolic coup

01:19:51.710 --> 01:19:53.970
of Mandela embracing
the sport that

01:19:53.970 --> 01:19:57.220
was the very symbol of
apartheid, of Mandela doing

01:19:57.220 --> 01:19:59.800
very subtle things
that a number of people

01:19:59.800 --> 01:20:02.270
pointed out who were
involved in the negotiations.

01:20:02.270 --> 01:20:05.330
OK, Mandela, just when
he's gotten out of prison,

01:20:05.330 --> 01:20:07.550
and he's about to meet
with some of the leaders

01:20:07.550 --> 01:20:10.170
of the government, and some of
the most right wing opponents

01:20:10.170 --> 01:20:11.290
to any sort of peace.

01:20:11.290 --> 01:20:13.300
And so we need a
conference room.

01:20:13.300 --> 01:20:15.090
And, no, that's not what he did.

01:20:15.090 --> 01:20:19.170
He insisted they would have the
meetings in his home, his home

01:20:19.170 --> 01:20:21.040
that he had just returned to.

01:20:21.040 --> 01:20:24.110
OK, well let's clear off
the dining room table.

01:20:24.110 --> 01:20:26.190
No, that's not what he did.

01:20:26.190 --> 01:20:29.440
He would insist they did this
in the living room, where

01:20:29.440 --> 01:20:33.180
they would sit down on
stuffed armchairs and couches.

01:20:33.180 --> 01:20:36.180
And something that he did,
apparently, always at these

01:20:36.180 --> 01:20:40.050
is he would sit down on the
couch, and gesture to whoever

01:20:40.050 --> 01:20:43.275
was likely to be the
most impossible foe,

01:20:43.275 --> 01:20:44.730
and say, come sit next to me.

01:20:44.730 --> 01:20:46.340
Sit next to me on the couch.

01:20:46.340 --> 01:20:49.890
And would proceed to jump
up at various points to say,

01:20:49.890 --> 01:20:51.580
can I get you some more tea?

01:20:51.580 --> 01:20:53.720
Do you want some more--
there would be food.

01:20:53.720 --> 01:20:54.790
There would be biscuits.

01:20:54.790 --> 01:20:58.010
There would be whatever--
brilliant, brilliant use

01:20:58.010 --> 01:20:59.090
of symbols.

01:20:59.090 --> 01:21:00.700
If I'm sitting
here, and this guy

01:21:00.700 --> 01:21:03.920
keeps jumping up and getting
me more cookies just when I

01:21:03.920 --> 01:21:06.530
was getting a hankering
for some more cookies,

01:21:06.530 --> 01:21:09.150
maybe not so
different after all.

01:21:09.150 --> 01:21:12.160
People who get cookies
for other people

01:21:12.160 --> 01:21:15.410
make the world more peaceful,
or something or other.

01:21:15.410 --> 01:21:17.610
What Axelrod has also
shown in some of his work

01:21:17.610 --> 01:21:20.910
is the potential for it--
really interesting stuff.

01:21:20.910 --> 01:21:23.960
He will, for example, he
and people working with him,

01:21:23.960 --> 01:21:28.390
have interviewed, say, Hamas
leaders in Palestinian,

01:21:28.390 --> 01:21:32.710
and the Gaza, and the West
Bank, some of the most

01:21:32.710 --> 01:21:36.380
opposed to the existence of
Israel, most confrontational

01:21:36.380 --> 01:21:36.880
of groups.

01:21:36.880 --> 01:21:40.660
And he gets quotes from their
leaders along the lines of,

01:21:40.660 --> 01:21:43.840
if the Israelis would
ever once just say,

01:21:43.840 --> 01:21:46.390
we got screwed in 1948.

01:21:46.390 --> 01:21:48.120
And we're sorry it happened.

01:21:48.120 --> 01:21:50.290
We would be willing
to make peace.

01:21:50.290 --> 01:21:53.412
And then he goes and talks
to some Israeli generals

01:21:53.412 --> 01:21:55.120
who are some of the
most right wing ones.

01:21:55.120 --> 01:21:56.240
He selects them for that.

01:21:56.240 --> 01:21:57.310
And they sit there.

01:21:57.310 --> 01:22:01.150
And they say stuff like, if the
damn Palestinians would ever

01:22:01.150 --> 01:22:04.380
just get the anti-Semitic
garbage out of their school

01:22:04.380 --> 01:22:07.430
books, we'd be able to
think seriously about peace

01:22:07.430 --> 01:22:08.320
the next day.

01:22:08.320 --> 01:22:10.260
It's not about water rights.

01:22:10.260 --> 01:22:12.690
It's not about return of land.

01:22:12.690 --> 01:22:15.510
It's just about, are
they going to respect

01:22:15.510 --> 01:22:18.880
our symbols and the
legitimacy of our history,

01:22:18.880 --> 01:22:20.640
and the accuracy of it?

01:22:20.640 --> 01:22:25.490
Enormously, potentially
powerful interventions there.

01:22:25.490 --> 01:22:30.730
OK, so kin selection-- most
importantly, pseudo kinship.

01:22:30.730 --> 01:22:33.260
Moving on now--
reciprocal altruism.

01:22:33.260 --> 01:22:36.490
Where does that come in, in
terms of potentially making

01:22:36.490 --> 01:22:37.520
for more peace?

01:22:37.520 --> 01:22:39.660
And what's clear
is, in principle,

01:22:39.660 --> 01:22:43.320
it should never do it if you
are playing only a single round

01:22:43.320 --> 01:22:45.810
of a game with someone, a
game in the prisoner's dilemma

01:22:45.810 --> 01:22:49.850
sense, because there's
absolutely no reason

01:22:49.850 --> 01:22:52.390
to cooperate,
because you are never

01:22:52.390 --> 01:22:54.190
going to face the person again.

01:22:54.190 --> 01:22:56.840
And this is something that was
called by a zoologist Garret

01:22:56.840 --> 01:22:59.790
Hardin the tragedy
of the commons,

01:22:59.790 --> 01:23:02.660
and the circumstance
of shared resources

01:23:02.660 --> 01:23:07.160
but limited responsibility, and
limited repeated interactions.

01:23:07.160 --> 01:23:09.510
You have to select
for selfishness.

01:23:09.510 --> 01:23:13.180
You have to select for what
is termed a Nash equilibrium,

01:23:13.180 --> 01:23:15.520
where the only possible
rational thing to do

01:23:15.520 --> 01:23:17.910
there is to not cooperate.

01:23:17.910 --> 01:23:20.580
So how do you ever
get cooperation

01:23:20.580 --> 01:23:24.270
to evolve in groups
of organisms?

01:23:24.270 --> 01:23:28.450
So back to the same Axelrod,
his work with computer

01:23:28.450 --> 01:23:30.290
tournaments there,
with a tit for tat,

01:23:30.290 --> 01:23:33.070
seeing that under some
circumstances one of them

01:23:33.070 --> 01:23:33.880
can dominate.

01:23:33.880 --> 01:23:35.610
Tit for tat is a
great optimal one.

01:23:35.610 --> 01:23:37.700
In the real world,
though, how do you ever

01:23:37.700 --> 01:23:40.230
jump start cooperation?

01:23:40.230 --> 01:23:43.100
How do you ever get one
of those strategies going

01:23:43.100 --> 01:23:46.650
when the starting state is
complete lack of cooperation?

01:23:46.650 --> 01:23:50.210
We already know one example,
which is founder populations,

01:23:50.210 --> 01:23:53.770
that whole business about get
an isolated population has

01:23:53.770 --> 01:23:57.340
a higher coefficient
of relatedness, inbred,

01:23:57.340 --> 01:23:58.800
out of kin selection.

01:23:58.800 --> 01:24:00.790
Establish high degrees
of cooperation.

01:24:00.790 --> 01:24:01.670
They come back.

01:24:01.670 --> 01:24:05.405
And it's this group
selection phenomenon of,

01:24:05.405 --> 01:24:07.570
you better become as
cooperative as them.

01:24:07.570 --> 01:24:10.240
Or you're not going
to be able to compete.

01:24:10.240 --> 01:24:12.090
And you could see
the same exact thing

01:24:12.090 --> 01:24:15.030
in circumstances where
it is not a founder

01:24:15.030 --> 01:24:17.250
effect of a population
goes away for a while

01:24:17.250 --> 01:24:20.590
and then comes back, but where
a population is functioning

01:24:20.590 --> 01:24:24.490
in that way amid a sea
of non-cooperators.

01:24:24.490 --> 01:24:27.280
In New York City
in the 1980s, there

01:24:27.280 --> 01:24:29.760
was this totally
weird phenomenon

01:24:29.760 --> 01:24:32.600
in that there were
two ethnic groups that

01:24:32.600 --> 01:24:35.250
were moving into New York
at a much higher rate

01:24:35.250 --> 01:24:37.250
than in the past--
Korean immigrants

01:24:37.250 --> 01:24:38.470
and Lebanese immigrants.

01:24:38.470 --> 01:24:41.450
And both groups happened to
gravitate towards grocery

01:24:41.450 --> 01:24:45.320
stores-- the Korean community
fruit, vegetable stands,

01:24:45.320 --> 01:24:48.570
the Lebanese community more
regular old grocery stores.

01:24:48.570 --> 01:24:51.890
And they were
incredibly successful.

01:24:51.890 --> 01:24:54.480
And these popped up
all over the place.

01:24:54.480 --> 01:24:58.080
And the people who already
had the fruit and vegetable

01:24:58.080 --> 01:25:01.020
stands and stuff started
complaining that they

01:25:01.020 --> 01:25:03.420
were at an unfair disadvantage.

01:25:03.420 --> 01:25:04.220
How come?

01:25:04.220 --> 01:25:07.670
Because these Korean
shop owners would

01:25:07.670 --> 01:25:09.230
cooperate with each other.

01:25:09.230 --> 01:25:12.070
They would give each
other interest-free loans.

01:25:12.070 --> 01:25:14.150
That's not fair.

01:25:14.150 --> 01:25:16.690
That's not fair that they're
being nice to each other.

01:25:16.690 --> 01:25:18.190
We can't compete.

01:25:18.190 --> 01:25:20.970
And the same thing with the
Lebanese grocery owners,

01:25:20.970 --> 01:25:23.990
that you had people
doing reciprocal altruism

01:25:23.990 --> 01:25:25.400
in a community of trust.

01:25:25.400 --> 01:25:27.150
And what they were
immediately doing

01:25:27.150 --> 01:25:30.360
was out competing
the non-cooperators.

01:25:30.360 --> 01:25:35.190
And amid these bizarre demands
for, like, banning Korean fruit

01:25:35.190 --> 01:25:37.560
and vegetable stands,
or some-- like,

01:25:37.560 --> 01:25:39.860
this was a point
of great hostility

01:25:39.860 --> 01:25:41.630
during that period
in New York City

01:25:41.630 --> 01:25:43.950
because those people
were cheating.

01:25:43.950 --> 01:25:45.980
They cooperated with each other.

01:25:45.980 --> 01:25:47.810
So either join in.

01:25:47.810 --> 01:25:50.770
Or you will be
driven to extinction.

01:25:50.770 --> 01:25:52.350
So that is one possibility.

01:25:52.350 --> 01:25:55.760
What are the other circumstances
in formal game theory

01:25:55.760 --> 01:26:00.000
play that favors the
emergence of cooperation?

01:26:00.000 --> 01:26:03.160
Critical one--
repetition, that you're

01:26:03.160 --> 01:26:07.380
going to play against this
individual more than just once.

01:26:07.380 --> 01:26:10.270
If it's run time, it's
tragedy of the commons.

01:26:10.270 --> 01:26:16.400
There is absolutely no reason
to select for cooperation.

01:26:16.400 --> 01:26:19.710
Repeated interactions,
and it opens up

01:26:19.710 --> 01:26:22.590
the possibility of
you being punished

01:26:22.590 --> 01:26:25.180
for being a cheater,
what they call

01:26:25.180 --> 01:26:29.810
the shadow of
future retribution.

01:26:29.810 --> 01:26:32.340
One qualifier with
that, though-- you

01:26:32.340 --> 01:26:34.940
need to have multiple
rounds of interactions.

01:26:34.940 --> 01:26:38.650
But it can't be a
known number of rounds.

01:26:38.650 --> 01:26:41.740
You can't know how many
rounds it's going to be.

01:26:41.740 --> 01:26:43.480
Think through this.

01:26:43.480 --> 01:26:46.540
You know that this is
the very last round

01:26:46.540 --> 01:26:48.010
you are going to play.

01:26:48.010 --> 01:26:51.230
And what's the only logical
thing to do is to cheat?

01:26:51.230 --> 01:26:53.360
The very last round
functions as if it

01:26:53.360 --> 01:26:56.960
was a tragedy of the commons
single game, single round game.

01:26:56.960 --> 01:26:58.610
So the only logical
thing to do is

01:26:58.610 --> 01:27:00.740
to cheat in the very last round.

01:27:00.740 --> 01:27:03.050
In which case, the only
logical thing to do

01:27:03.050 --> 01:27:05.190
is to cheat in the
next to the last round,

01:27:05.190 --> 01:27:06.310
and the next to the last.

01:27:06.310 --> 01:27:09.540
A known number of
rounds of interactions

01:27:09.540 --> 01:27:12.610
immediately does in
cooperation because it sort of

01:27:12.610 --> 01:27:17.320
flows backwards with this
collapse of the system.

01:27:17.320 --> 01:27:20.460
The next thing that favors it
is what is called open book

01:27:20.460 --> 01:27:23.210
play by people in the
business, which is you

01:27:23.210 --> 01:27:26.730
will be playing against a
number of different individuals,

01:27:26.730 --> 01:27:29.840
and pairs, cycling through.

01:27:29.840 --> 01:27:31.320
And the critical
thing is when you

01:27:31.320 --> 01:27:34.030
begin to play with
someone else, they

01:27:34.030 --> 01:27:38.590
can know your record as to how
you played in previous games.

01:27:38.590 --> 01:27:42.230
In other words, once
you bring in reputation,

01:27:42.230 --> 01:27:45.750
when reputation can be
possible, suddenly you

01:27:45.750 --> 01:27:48.640
select for cooperation.

01:27:48.640 --> 01:27:53.280
Next, what's shown is that
if you have people playing

01:27:53.280 --> 01:27:55.250
in multiple games
with each other,

01:27:55.250 --> 01:27:57.190
especially when
they're unsynchronized,

01:27:57.190 --> 01:27:59.610
you select for
cooperation as well.

01:27:59.610 --> 01:28:00.930
What's this about?

01:28:00.930 --> 01:28:04.580
What you do is if one of
the games makes it very,

01:28:04.580 --> 01:28:07.670
very easy in terms of
payoff for cooperation

01:28:07.670 --> 01:28:10.660
to get established,
if you intermix rounds

01:28:10.660 --> 01:28:14.440
of that game with a game in
which there is very little

01:28:14.440 --> 01:28:17.860
motivation for cooperation
starting, what you see

01:28:17.860 --> 01:28:20.390
is a psychological bleed over.

01:28:20.390 --> 01:28:23.890
If you are cooperating with
this person in this game, which

01:28:23.890 --> 01:28:26.360
is now done here now
down here, it greatly

01:28:26.360 --> 01:28:29.920
increases the odds of one doing
the other game of beginning

01:28:29.920 --> 01:28:31.620
to cooperate as well.

01:28:31.620 --> 01:28:33.920
Multiple games, and
it does not take

01:28:33.920 --> 01:28:37.070
much to see that this is
more like the real world

01:28:37.070 --> 01:28:40.840
than playing prisoner's dilemma
with one single individual.

01:28:40.840 --> 01:28:44.520
Next, the possibility
of punishing someone

01:28:44.520 --> 01:28:45.780
when they are a creep.

01:28:45.780 --> 01:28:47.930
And that's what we
heard about before, what

01:28:47.930 --> 01:28:51.000
is termed now in the field
altruistic punishment.

01:28:51.000 --> 01:28:53.440
If somebody does
something crummy to you,

01:28:53.440 --> 01:28:55.550
you are allowed to
expend a certain amount

01:28:55.550 --> 01:28:59.120
of your resources to take
more of the resources

01:28:59.120 --> 01:29:00.650
away from them.

01:29:00.650 --> 01:29:02.880
That selects for cooperation.

01:29:02.880 --> 01:29:05.120
Something that
even selects faster

01:29:05.120 --> 01:29:08.380
is second party
altruistic punishing.

01:29:08.380 --> 01:29:10.900
You are not taking
part in the game.

01:29:10.900 --> 01:29:12.770
You're watching these
two individuals,

01:29:12.770 --> 01:29:15.680
But you have the power to
use some of your resources

01:29:15.680 --> 01:29:19.580
to punish a cheater--
an outside enforcer.

01:29:19.580 --> 01:29:23.760
That selects for
cooperation even faster.

01:29:23.760 --> 01:29:27.360
Then something that is even
more effective, which is

01:29:27.360 --> 01:29:30.620
termed secondary
altruistic punishing.

01:29:30.620 --> 01:29:32.080
Here's what you do.

01:29:32.080 --> 01:29:35.310
What you do is
people are observers

01:29:35.310 --> 01:29:37.970
of other people's interactions,
and seeing if they're cheating.

01:29:37.970 --> 01:29:40.177
And they can do some
altruistic punishment

01:29:40.177 --> 01:29:42.510
if they think this individual
is a jerk and all of that.

01:29:42.510 --> 01:29:43.970
But here's what you do.

01:29:43.970 --> 01:29:47.250
If there is a circumstance
where somebody cheats

01:29:47.250 --> 01:29:51.270
and this third party
individual doesn't punish them,

01:29:51.270 --> 01:29:53.230
they get punished.

01:29:53.230 --> 01:29:54.690
What's that about?

01:29:54.690 --> 01:29:56.920
That's honor code violations.

01:29:56.920 --> 01:29:59.270
That's the expectation
that you are

01:29:59.270 --> 01:30:01.850
supposed to report someone
who has had an honor code

01:30:01.850 --> 01:30:02.670
violation.

01:30:02.670 --> 01:30:05.470
And if you don't, you
will get punished.

01:30:05.470 --> 01:30:09.230
That selects for cooperation
really fast also.

01:30:09.230 --> 01:30:12.660
And all of these-- these have
been computer tournaments,

01:30:12.660 --> 01:30:13.690
and all of that.

01:30:13.690 --> 01:30:16.440
You know that world
of research by now.

01:30:16.440 --> 01:30:19.750
Finally, more subtle
stuff, gives the person

01:30:19.750 --> 01:30:22.070
the opportunity to
drop out of the game,

01:30:22.070 --> 01:30:23.620
to secede from the game.

01:30:23.620 --> 01:30:26.920
Give the person the opportunity
to not play against you,

01:30:26.920 --> 01:30:29.750
but to choose, I'll play against
all these other individuals,

01:30:29.750 --> 01:30:30.830
but not that one.

01:30:30.830 --> 01:30:32.810
Begin to put that
power in there.

01:30:32.810 --> 01:30:37.220
And you select for
cooperation that much faster.

01:30:37.220 --> 01:30:40.690
So that's some good news.

01:30:40.690 --> 01:30:44.030
Final level, the group selection
level-- group selection

01:30:44.030 --> 01:30:46.270
not in our behaving for
the good of the species,

01:30:46.270 --> 01:30:49.240
but as we know the more
modern version of it,

01:30:49.240 --> 01:30:51.150
selection for
traits that are only

01:30:51.150 --> 01:30:54.400
manifest at the level
of whole groups.

01:30:54.400 --> 01:30:59.710
A always loses to B. But groups
of A always defeat groups of B.

01:30:59.710 --> 01:31:01.340
All of the stuff
we've been seeing,

01:31:01.340 --> 01:31:05.360
people suddenly cooperating with
each other as a small group,

01:31:05.360 --> 01:31:08.530
and driving the non-cooperators
out of business,

01:31:08.530 --> 01:31:11.780
that's a group selection
argument going on there.

01:31:11.780 --> 01:31:14.880
So you can have that as
a means for generating

01:31:14.880 --> 01:31:16.390
a lot of cooperation.

01:31:16.390 --> 01:31:17.390
That's great.

01:31:17.390 --> 01:31:19.170
That makes the world
a better place,

01:31:19.170 --> 01:31:21.630
unless there is
a downside to it.

01:31:21.630 --> 01:31:24.580
And back to
chimpanzees, what do you

01:31:24.580 --> 01:31:27.390
have when a bunch
of related chimps

01:31:27.390 --> 01:31:31.180
are having not individual fights
with males from the next valley

01:31:31.180 --> 01:31:33.110
over, but functioning
as a group?

01:31:33.110 --> 01:31:36.060
You are having an example
of group selection, which

01:31:36.060 --> 01:31:40.380
thus brings up one of the
most profoundly scary things

01:31:40.380 --> 01:31:42.380
on this planet,
which is when you've

01:31:42.380 --> 01:31:43.970
got a bunch of males
who are getting

01:31:43.970 --> 01:31:45.522
along well with each other.

01:31:45.522 --> 01:31:47.480
And they're beginning to
look at the neighbors,

01:31:47.480 --> 01:31:50.250
because lots of males
cooperating together

01:31:50.250 --> 01:31:52.370
can make for some
very bad neighbors.

01:31:52.370 --> 01:31:55.130
As some people in the
field have emphasized,

01:31:55.130 --> 01:31:57.740
a decrease in homicide
within a group

01:31:57.740 --> 01:32:01.660
is a prerequisite for inventing
genocide between groups.

01:32:01.660 --> 01:32:05.530
So group selection is not always
this magical founder effect

01:32:05.530 --> 01:32:08.240
of everybody wanting to
learn the new folk songs.

01:32:08.240 --> 01:32:10.190
What you've got instead
are circumstances

01:32:10.190 --> 01:32:12.810
where it can go very wrong.

01:32:12.810 --> 01:32:16.530
Final amazing example
showing the emergence

01:32:16.530 --> 01:32:19.340
of cooperation--
and this was not

01:32:19.340 --> 01:32:21.000
a game theory demonstration.

01:32:21.000 --> 01:32:22.460
This was not an experiment.

01:32:22.460 --> 01:32:25.340
This was a real
event that happened,

01:32:25.340 --> 01:32:27.320
and an extraordinary one.

01:32:27.320 --> 01:32:32.040
This occurred during World
War I. A lot of people

01:32:32.040 --> 01:32:34.310
have heard about a phenomenon
that happened there,

01:32:34.310 --> 01:32:37.680
a historical incident
that was very, very cruel,

01:32:37.680 --> 01:32:41.220
but pales in comparison to
what I'm about to tell about.

01:32:41.220 --> 01:32:45.220
In 1914, the first Christmas
of World War I, somehow

01:32:45.220 --> 01:32:46.970
the decision was made
that there was going

01:32:46.970 --> 01:32:49.010
to be a truce on Christmas Day.

01:32:49.010 --> 01:32:51.600
All of the fighting up
and down the trenches

01:32:51.600 --> 01:32:53.830
was going to cease for 24 hours.

01:32:53.830 --> 01:32:55.410
And it has been documented.

01:32:55.410 --> 01:32:58.130
It was amazing and bizarre.

01:32:58.130 --> 01:33:00.810
Men out of the
trenches playing soccer

01:33:00.810 --> 01:33:04.580
with each other from different
sides-- a bunch of German

01:33:04.580 --> 01:33:08.570
and French guys playing against
some British and German guys

01:33:08.570 --> 01:33:11.850
on the other side,
people exchanging gifts,

01:33:11.850 --> 01:33:15.100
people exchanging
helmets as souvenirs,

01:33:15.100 --> 01:33:18.170
people singing together,
people getting drunk together

01:33:18.170 --> 01:33:19.970
from the two opposite sides.

01:33:19.970 --> 01:33:22.620
And, eventually,
when the officers

01:33:22.620 --> 01:33:24.790
got them to go
back to their job,

01:33:24.790 --> 01:33:29.490
they returned to trying to kill
each other-- amazing, bizarre

01:33:29.490 --> 01:33:29.990
incident.

01:33:29.990 --> 01:33:32.850
What was very striking
about it is it extended,

01:33:32.850 --> 01:33:35.320
actually, two or three
days extra longer than

01:33:35.320 --> 01:33:37.400
planned because the
officers couldn't

01:33:37.400 --> 01:33:40.180
get people to stop doing this.

01:33:40.180 --> 01:33:41.370
That's very cool.

01:33:41.370 --> 01:33:45.190
But that's an outside
force already establishing

01:33:45.190 --> 01:33:46.570
the cooperation.

01:33:46.570 --> 01:33:49.690
Here's something much,
much more impressive.

01:33:49.690 --> 01:33:51.610
And this happened
in World War I.

01:33:51.610 --> 01:33:54.280
And it didn't take a bunch of
generals or heads of states

01:33:54.280 --> 01:33:58.240
to negotiate a truce--
the way in which truces

01:33:58.240 --> 01:34:01.970
would spontaneously
merge over and over again

01:34:01.970 --> 01:34:03.660
across the trenches.

01:34:03.660 --> 01:34:07.010
How do you generate a
reciprocally altruistic

01:34:07.010 --> 01:34:09.530
cooperative relationship
with the enemy

01:34:09.530 --> 01:34:11.190
in the trenches
over there, where

01:34:11.190 --> 01:34:12.600
you don't speak
the same language

01:34:12.600 --> 01:34:14.640
and you don't even
see their faces?

01:34:14.640 --> 01:34:16.470
Here's what you do.

01:34:16.470 --> 01:34:18.530
You take your best gunner.

01:34:18.530 --> 01:34:21.740
And have him come
up and lob a shell

01:34:21.740 --> 01:34:26.090
20 yards behind the trench
there, and blow up a tree.

01:34:26.090 --> 01:34:30.150
Now have you gunner lob a shell
to hit the exact same spot

01:34:30.150 --> 01:34:32.870
again, and do it
again, and do it again.

01:34:32.870 --> 01:34:34.240
Do it a bunch of times.

01:34:34.240 --> 01:34:36.840
What are you communicating
to the other side?

01:34:36.840 --> 01:34:38.800
This guy's really good.

01:34:38.800 --> 01:34:42.780
And we're choosing not to put
the missile down on top of you.

01:34:42.780 --> 01:34:44.540
What are you going
to do about it?

01:34:44.540 --> 01:34:47.650
And then the other side would
get out their best gunner

01:34:47.650 --> 01:34:49.320
and do the thing in return.

01:34:49.320 --> 01:34:53.270
And you have just worked
out a non-aggression pact.

01:34:53.270 --> 01:34:55.710
And this occurred
over and over again

01:34:55.710 --> 01:34:58.840
in the trench warfare,
documented in letters

01:34:58.840 --> 01:35:01.730
by soldiers back home
to parents, saying,

01:35:01.730 --> 01:35:03.080
hi Mom and Dad.

01:35:03.080 --> 01:35:04.610
Things are OK here.

01:35:04.610 --> 01:35:06.360
I hope you're worrying
less, because we've

01:35:06.360 --> 01:35:07.740
worked out something.

01:35:07.740 --> 01:35:09.650
Things are a lot better here.

01:35:09.650 --> 01:35:12.430
There's a lot less
people getting hurt.

01:35:12.430 --> 01:35:16.100
Working it out along those
lines, working out a tit

01:35:16.100 --> 01:35:18.830
for tat vulnerability
where you had

01:35:18.830 --> 01:35:22.820
to have a forgiving tit
for tat, what if somebody

01:35:22.820 --> 01:35:24.910
messed up and
accidentally dropped

01:35:24.910 --> 01:35:27.510
a shell into the trench
on the other side?

01:35:27.510 --> 01:35:30.270
They got one shot back.

01:35:30.270 --> 01:35:33.270
Letters, dear Mom and
Dad, things are OK here.

01:35:33.270 --> 01:35:35.004
We had an incident
the other day.

01:35:35.004 --> 01:35:36.670
We had this new gunner
who didn't really

01:35:36.670 --> 01:35:38.240
understand how things worked.

01:35:38.240 --> 01:35:40.670
And I heard he killed
four people on their side.

01:35:40.670 --> 01:35:41.720
They shot one back.

01:35:41.720 --> 01:35:43.136
They took out three
of our people.

01:35:43.136 --> 01:35:44.940
But everything is OK now.

01:35:44.940 --> 01:35:48.250
Tit for tat, complete
with a forgiving element--

01:35:48.250 --> 01:35:51.490
this happened again,
and again, and again,

01:35:51.490 --> 01:35:52.860
in the trench warfare.

01:35:52.860 --> 01:35:55.750
And the only thing that
stopped it from spreading

01:35:55.750 --> 01:35:57.760
is the fact that
the officers kept

01:35:57.760 --> 01:36:00.450
insisting that nobody
else was doing this.

01:36:00.450 --> 01:36:03.130
And these guys were going to
get shot and court marshaled

01:36:03.130 --> 01:36:05.070
if they didn't stop this.

01:36:05.070 --> 01:36:08.190
And if they had only
had cell phones,

01:36:08.190 --> 01:36:11.100
if they only had
communication, if they only

01:36:11.100 --> 01:36:13.840
had a way of knowing
up and down the line

01:36:13.840 --> 01:36:16.170
that everybody was
doing this, they

01:36:16.170 --> 01:36:19.000
would have stopped the
war-- not with a treaty,

01:36:19.000 --> 01:36:21.010
not with generals, not
with heads of state,

01:36:21.010 --> 01:36:23.710
not with diplomats,
but simply a bottom

01:36:23.710 --> 01:36:26.510
up way of evolving cooperation.

01:36:26.510 --> 01:36:28.340
And they would have
stopped the war

01:36:28.340 --> 01:36:31.030
if they knew that they
weren't the only ones wanting

01:36:31.030 --> 01:36:35.920
to do this-- amazing
historical incident.

01:36:35.920 --> 01:36:38.840
OK, so this gets us to
the end of aggression.

01:36:38.840 --> 01:36:41.640
As you probably noticed,
this has gone on way long.

01:36:41.640 --> 01:36:43.560
This is the longest
amount of material

01:36:43.560 --> 01:36:45.270
we spend on anything
in the course.

01:36:45.270 --> 01:36:47.700
And each year, it
actually gets longer.

01:36:47.700 --> 01:36:50.920
And I actually think I
know the reason for it.

01:36:50.920 --> 01:36:52.420
Three and a half
lectures ago, where

01:36:52.420 --> 01:36:56.280
did I start off talking
about my recent exposure

01:36:56.280 --> 01:36:58.520
to human aggression,
which was my doing it,

01:36:58.520 --> 01:37:00.670
and tripping up that
jerk playing soccer.

01:37:00.670 --> 01:37:02.570
And everybody was all excited.

01:37:02.570 --> 01:37:05.010
Let me tell you
about another time,

01:37:05.010 --> 01:37:06.620
the most serious
time I have ever been

01:37:06.620 --> 01:37:09.120
exposed to human aggression.

01:37:09.120 --> 01:37:11.686
This took place
when I was about 20.

01:37:11.686 --> 01:37:14.420
And this was first
year that I was

01:37:14.420 --> 01:37:16.200
doing research in East Africa.

01:37:16.200 --> 01:37:20.100
During that time, the famed
notorious dictator Idi Amin

01:37:20.100 --> 01:37:21.620
was running Uganda.

01:37:21.620 --> 01:37:23.930
And he was a nightmare.

01:37:23.930 --> 01:37:26.810
He was just killing
people left and right,

01:37:26.810 --> 01:37:30.270
destroying the country, as
documented, cannibalizing.

01:37:30.270 --> 01:37:32.670
Was a nightmare of a dictator.

01:37:32.670 --> 01:37:34.710
Around the time,
he made a mistake.

01:37:34.710 --> 01:37:39.359
This was spring of 1979, which
is he invaded Tanzania and took

01:37:39.359 --> 01:37:40.900
over some of the
land there, thinking

01:37:40.900 --> 01:37:42.660
the Tanzanians
wouldn't fight back.

01:37:42.660 --> 01:37:44.680
And he miscalculated.

01:37:44.680 --> 01:37:48.250
The Tanzania army
counterattacked, and drove them

01:37:48.250 --> 01:37:52.110
out of Uganda, and decided to
drive all the way to Kampala,

01:37:52.110 --> 01:37:53.440
the capital of Uganda.

01:37:53.440 --> 01:37:55.510
And they overthrew Idi Amin.

01:37:55.510 --> 01:37:56.930
He fled the country.

01:37:56.930 --> 01:37:59.210
And the country was liberated.

01:37:59.210 --> 01:38:00.590
They continued through there.

01:38:00.590 --> 01:38:03.610
And they opened up a corridor
to the Kenyan border.

01:38:03.610 --> 01:38:05.930
So it was now a swath all
through the southern part

01:38:05.930 --> 01:38:08.790
of the country that was
controlled by Tanzania.

01:38:08.790 --> 01:38:11.560
So the day after the
Tanzanians got things

01:38:11.560 --> 01:38:15.040
to the Kenyan border,
I went into Uganda.

01:38:15.040 --> 01:38:16.800
OK, why?

01:38:16.800 --> 01:38:19.340
This was amazing.

01:38:19.340 --> 01:38:20.630
This was history happening.

01:38:20.630 --> 01:38:23.870
You were hearing on the BBC
that people were dancing

01:38:23.870 --> 01:38:25.440
in the streets in Kampala.

01:38:25.440 --> 01:38:28.940
They had been liberated,
amazing chance to see history.

01:38:28.940 --> 01:38:30.550
This was-- through
our college, I

01:38:30.550 --> 01:38:33.240
had been spending a lot
of time with Quakers,

01:38:33.240 --> 01:38:36.160
and wrestling with those
issues, and figured

01:38:36.160 --> 01:38:38.530
if there is anything that
counts as a just war,

01:38:38.530 --> 01:38:39.370
this would be it.

01:38:39.370 --> 01:38:40.780
What does this seem like?

01:38:40.780 --> 01:38:42.692
All these philosophical
principles.

01:38:42.692 --> 01:38:44.900
This, actually, of course,
was not what was going on.

01:38:44.900 --> 01:38:47.360
I was a 20-year-old male.

01:38:47.360 --> 01:38:50.780
And somebody had been staying
with me, and no longer was.

01:38:50.780 --> 01:38:52.120
And I was all bummed out.

01:38:52.120 --> 01:38:55.370
And, thus, I did sort of
a very 20-year-old male

01:38:55.370 --> 01:38:58.400
adolescent primate thing,
which is figuring some violence

01:38:58.400 --> 01:39:00.960
would do some good things
for my brain neurochemistry.

01:39:00.960 --> 01:39:03.290
And I wanted to go see a war.

01:39:03.290 --> 01:39:05.910
So I went off to Uganda,
hitching through there.

01:39:05.910 --> 01:39:08.930
And it was
appropriately exciting.

01:39:08.930 --> 01:39:11.850
And some things happened that
scared the bejesus out of me.

01:39:11.850 --> 01:39:14.576
And at some point, I finally
decided I have had enough.

01:39:14.576 --> 01:39:15.700
I want to go back to Kenya.

01:39:15.700 --> 01:39:16.956
I want to feel safe again.

01:39:16.956 --> 01:39:17.830
So I'm hitching back.

01:39:17.830 --> 01:39:19.620
But I had one last
thing that I want

01:39:19.620 --> 01:39:21.930
to do, which was
since I was a kid,

01:39:21.930 --> 01:39:23.850
I had grown up reading
about the explorers,

01:39:23.850 --> 01:39:26.400
and the search for the source
of the Nile and all of that.

01:39:26.400 --> 01:39:30.210
The source of the white
Nile is in Uganda.

01:39:30.210 --> 01:39:34.020
It comes out of Lake Victoria
in a town called Tororo.

01:39:34.020 --> 01:39:36.250
And there's a spot
there, a bridge

01:39:36.250 --> 01:39:37.900
where you can go and stand.

01:39:37.900 --> 01:39:40.950
And here is where the
Nile River begins.

01:39:40.950 --> 01:39:43.080
And I had to see
this before leaving.

01:39:43.080 --> 01:39:45.160
And I managed to get
a ride into there.

01:39:45.160 --> 01:39:48.810
And I managed to get over to
this bridge, and stood there.

01:39:48.810 --> 01:39:52.179
And there was this
sort of dam thing

01:39:52.179 --> 01:39:53.970
that was built that
this bridge was on top.

01:39:53.970 --> 01:39:56.660
And there was this sluice where
all the water came spritzing

01:39:56.660 --> 01:39:58.160
out, and started the Nile.

01:39:58.160 --> 01:39:58.910
And I stood there.

01:39:58.910 --> 01:40:00.420
And I looked over the side.

01:40:00.420 --> 01:40:04.280
And what I saw was there
was a Ugandan soldier

01:40:04.280 --> 01:40:05.620
who had been taken down there.

01:40:05.620 --> 01:40:09.070
There was a staircase along the
side down to some sort of panel

01:40:09.070 --> 01:40:11.400
for controls or whatever.

01:40:11.400 --> 01:40:13.710
And a Ugandan soldier
had been taken down

01:40:13.710 --> 01:40:16.420
the steps, his hands
tied behind his back,

01:40:16.420 --> 01:40:18.470
and a rope tied
around his throat

01:40:18.470 --> 01:40:20.230
and attached to the panel.

01:40:20.230 --> 01:40:22.430
So that as the
water level rose, he

01:40:22.430 --> 01:40:24.530
would eventually be
swept off his feet

01:40:24.530 --> 01:40:28.310
and would be strangled
and drowned in the water.

01:40:28.310 --> 01:40:31.270
And this body had obviously
been there for days.

01:40:31.270 --> 01:40:32.580
It was bloated.

01:40:32.580 --> 01:40:33.970
It was floating there.

01:40:33.970 --> 01:40:35.940
It was being bashed
around on the waves.

01:40:35.940 --> 01:40:38.140
There were crocs
trying to get at it.

01:40:38.140 --> 01:40:42.750
And looking at this guy, a total
storm of emotions-- thinking,

01:40:42.750 --> 01:40:46.910
good, that's what you deserve
being in the army for Amin.

01:40:46.910 --> 01:40:48.380
Then thinking,
no, wait a second.

01:40:48.380 --> 01:40:50.630
This is probably some poor
guy who was forced to do it

01:40:50.630 --> 01:40:52.260
and was just following orders.

01:40:52.260 --> 01:40:54.810
Then thinking, no, I know
what I think of soldiers

01:40:54.810 --> 01:40:56.200
who just follow orders.

01:40:56.200 --> 01:40:58.560
Then thinking, whoa, I would
love to get a lot closer

01:40:58.560 --> 01:41:00.060
and see what's
happening down there.

01:41:00.060 --> 01:41:02.700
And thinking, I want to get as
far away from here as possible.

01:41:02.700 --> 01:41:05.320
And I stood there for
an hour and a half

01:41:05.320 --> 01:41:10.010
at that spot staring at this guy
until some Tanzanian soldiers

01:41:10.010 --> 01:41:11.750
chased me away from there.

01:41:11.750 --> 01:41:15.300
And I think now, 33
years later, that I

01:41:15.300 --> 01:41:18.800
lecture longer and longer about
aggression each year because

01:41:18.800 --> 01:41:20.390
of that guy.

01:41:20.390 --> 01:41:22.930
What do we do here
in our business?

01:41:22.930 --> 01:41:26.320
We have this general notion
that if we are rational,

01:41:26.320 --> 01:41:28.870
if we are learned,
if we are scholarly,

01:41:28.870 --> 01:41:31.640
if we respect thoughts
and truth and all of that,

01:41:31.640 --> 01:41:33.920
we will make the
world a better place.

01:41:33.920 --> 01:41:36.640
All of us who are professorial
have somewhere in there

01:41:36.640 --> 01:41:39.090
this totally ridiculous
belief that if you're

01:41:39.090 --> 01:41:41.770
allowed to lecture at
a subject long enough,

01:41:41.770 --> 01:41:43.580
it will give up and go away.

01:41:43.580 --> 01:41:45.630
And that will be the cure
for world aggression.

01:41:45.630 --> 01:41:47.300
If everybody can
only be lectured

01:41:47.300 --> 01:41:51.740
to about the frontal cortex,
it will solve world violence.

01:41:51.740 --> 01:41:54.280
But the basic problem
is that aggression is

01:41:54.280 --> 01:41:57.250
such a messy set of behaviors.

01:41:57.250 --> 01:42:00.900
Schizophrenia-- no question
about it, bad news.

01:42:00.900 --> 01:42:04.300
Alzheimer's disease, childhood
cancer, global warming,

01:42:04.300 --> 01:42:07.610
all of these
unassailably bad news.

01:42:07.610 --> 01:42:10.710
But aggression is a whole
lot more complicated,

01:42:10.710 --> 01:42:13.190
because of that point
where we started with,

01:42:13.190 --> 01:42:16.420
which is the same
exact behaviors,

01:42:16.420 --> 01:42:18.530
and depending on the
context, it could

01:42:18.530 --> 01:42:21.870
be something that would get
a medal for someone, someone

01:42:21.870 --> 01:42:25.890
you will want to mate with, vote
for, reward, cheer on, join in.

01:42:25.890 --> 01:42:28.220
And in another setting,
it is the most frightening

01:42:28.220 --> 01:42:30.070
possible thing that
can happen to us.

01:42:30.070 --> 01:42:33.510
And it's the same behaviors
in all those cases.

01:42:33.510 --> 01:42:36.250
And it's for that reason,
that violence is always

01:42:36.250 --> 01:42:38.800
going to be the hardest
subject for us to understand

01:42:38.800 --> 01:42:39.880
biologically.

01:42:39.880 --> 01:42:42.340
And it's for that
reason, that it's always

01:42:42.340 --> 01:42:46.340
going to be the one we have
to try hardest to understand.

01:42:46.340 --> 01:42:49.550
For more, please visit
us at Stanford.edu.

